{"title_page": "John Skene, Lord Curriehill", "text_new": "{{For|Deputy Governor of the West Jersey colony|John Skene (New Jersey)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n'''Sir John Skene, Lord Curriehill''' (1549&ndash;1617) was a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] prosecutor, ambassador, and judge. He was involved in the negotiations for the marriage of James VI and Anne of Denmark.\n[[File:The grave of John Skene, Lord Curriehill, Greyfriars Kirkyard, Edinburgh.jpg|thumb|300px|The grave of John Skene, Lord Curriehill, Greyfriars Kirkyard, Edinburgh]]\nHe was regent in [[St Mary's College, St Andrews]] from 1564-5 and became an [[Faculty of Advocates|advocate]] in 1575.\n\n==Life==\nHe was born in 1549. He was the sixth son of James Skene of Wester Corse (b.1505) and Janet Lumsden.<ref>https://www.clanmacfarlanegenealogy.info/genealogy/TNGWebsite/getperson.php?personID=I36978&tree=CC</ref> Their lands were at Bandodle or Wester Corse, a manor in Aberdeenshire.<ref>[https://canmore.org.uk/site/76536/wester-corse HES/RCAHMS Canmore: Wester Corse].</ref>\n\nIn his own writings he mentions his travels, describing the appearance of a travelling salesman in [[Krak\u00f3w]] in 1569. The writer [[Thomas Dempster]] mentions Skene's travels in the countries of Northern Europe and his fluency in their languages. [[James Melville of Halhill]] said he could give long speeches in Latin, and was \"good, true, and stout\".<ref>[https://archive.org/details/memorialsoffamil00sken/page/106 William Forbes Skene, ''Memorials of the family of Skene of Skene'' (Aberdeen, 1887), pp. 107-8].</ref>\n\nSkene enrolled or matriculated at the [[University of Wittenberg]] on 16 March 1570.<ref>David Scott Gehring, ''Diplomatic Intelligence on the Holy Roman Empire and Denmark during the Reigns of Elizabeth I and James VI'', Camden Fifth Series, 49 (2016), p. 156 fn. 32.</ref>\n\nSkene's career was advanced by the marriages of his sisters to [[Alexander Hay, Lord Fosterseat|Alexander Hay]], [[Lord Clerk Register]], and [[Walter Stewart, 1st Lord Blantyre|Lord Blantyre]], an exchequer official and one of the [[Octavians]].<ref>[https://archive.org/details/memorialsoffamil00sken/page/106 William Forbes Skene, ''Memorials of the family of Skene of Skene'' (Aberdeen, 1887), p. 106].</ref>\n\nAs joint [[Lord Advocate]] from 1589 to 1594, he was zealous in the [[Witch trials in early modern Scotland|prosecution of witches]]. He was appointed [[Lord Clerk Register]] and [[Court of Session|Lord of Session]], with the judicial title of Lord Curriehill in 1594, serving until 1611.\n\nAs a diplomat, Skene went to Denmark to seek an agreement over rights to [[Orkney]], and presented a memorandum on that topic to [[Sophie of Mecklenburg-G\u00fcstrow]] and the four regents of [[Christian IV of Denmark]] at [[Helsing\u00f8r]] on 20 August 1589. He was also given instructions to negotiate the terms of the royal marriage.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/calendarofmanusc03grea_1/page/420 ''Calendar of the manuscripts of the Most Honourable the Marquess of Salisbury preserved at Hatfield House'', vol. 3 (London, 1892), pp. 420-3].</ref> His companions were; [[George Keith, 5th Earl Marischal]], [[Andrew Keith, Lord Dingwall|Andrew Keith]], James Scrimgeour of [[Dudhope Castle|Dudhope]] the Constable of [[River Tay|Tay]] and standard bearer of Scotland, and [[George Young (diplomat)|George Young]].<ref>William Forbes Skene, ''Memorials of the family of Skene of Skene'' (Aberdeen, 1887), p. 109: ''Register of the Privy Council of Scotland'', vol. 4 (Edinburgh, 1881), pp. 822-4.</ref> He returned on to Scotland 23 July 1589 with his colleagues Andrew Keith, and George Young and went to [[James VI of Scotland]] at [[Boyne Castle]]. An English observer [[Thomas Fowler (courtier)|Thomas Fowler]] reported their news including the Danish opinion that James VI asked for too high a dowry, but they had seen extensive preparations for the marriage including a coach made of silver. According to their report, Anne of Denmark was keen for the marriage to go ahead, and Fowler wrote; \"the young lady is so far in love with the king's majesty as it were death to her to have it broken off, and has made good proof (in) diverse ways of her affection, which his majesty is apt enough to requite\".<ref>''Calendar of State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 124-7, quotation (modernised) p. 124, source [[British Library]] Egerton MS 2,598/16.</ref>\n\nOn 22 October 1589, he accompanied James VI on his voyage from Leith to Norway and Denmark to meet his wife [[Anne of Denmark]], and attended the meeting of the [[Privy Council of Scotland]] at Oslo on 25 November.<ref>''Register of the Privy Council of Scotland'', vol. 4 (Edinburgh, 1881), pp. 430, 438.</ref>\n\nJames VI had given Anne of Denmark a \"[[morning gift]]\" of lands and palaces. In the week before her coronation in Scotland the Danish ambassadors travelled to view these places and take formal possession. On 12 May 1589 the envoys were welcomed at [[Falkland Palace]] by the keeper, James Beaton of Creich. Skene produced a printed charter of the queen's lands in [[Fife, Scotland|Fife]] and as a traditional symbol of the transfer of ownership ([[sasine]]), the [[Admiral of the Realm|Danish Admiral]] [[Peder Munk]] was given a handful of earth. After this ceremony, the party rode to the Newhouse of [[Lochleven Castle]] to stay the night, then repeated the ritual at [[Dunfermline Palace]], and on 14 May at [[Linlithgow Palace]].<ref>David Stevenson, ''Scotland's Last Royal Wedding'' (John Donald: Edinburgh, 1997), pp. 102-3.</ref>\n\nIn June 1590 [[James VI of Scotland]] sent Skene and [[William Stewart of Houston|Colonel William Stewart]], [[Prior of May (Pittenweem)|Commendator of Pittenweem]], as ambassadors to Denmark and Germany.<ref>David Scott Gehring, \u2018ANE ACCOUNT OF ANE EMBASSIE\u2019, 1590' in ''Diplomatic Intelligence on the Holy Roman Empire and Denmark during the Reigns of Elizabeth I and James VI'', Camden Fifth Series, 49 (2016), pp. 151-217.</ref> The mission was to intended to cement a peaceful league in Europe.<ref>Thomas Rymer, ''Foedera'', vol. 16 (London, 1715), pp. 68-71: Annie I. Cameron, ''Warrender Papers'', vol. 2 (Edinburgh, 1932), pp. 133-41.</ref> They met the mother of [[Anne of Denmark]], [[Sophie of Mecklenburg-G\u00fcstrow]] at [[Braunschweig]], then went on to meet [[William IV, Landgrave of Hesse-Kassel]] at [[Rotenburg an der Fulda]] and [[Christian I, Elector of Saxony]] at Dresden. Skene was ill when he returned to Edinburgh.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 12 (Edinburgh, 1952), pp. 370, 384, 388, 492.</ref>\n\nHe served as ambassador to Holland from 1591.\n\nHis compilation of old Scots law ''[[Regiam Majestatem]]'' is a source of the laws of Scotland previous to [[James I of Scotland|James I]]. He was granted a pension by [[James Douglas, 4th Earl of Morton|Regent Morton]] for preparing a digest of laws. He also produced a [[Scots law]] dictionary, ''De Verborum Significatione''. According to the Dictionary of National Biography, \"In 1592 he was named one of a commission to examine the laws and acts of parliament, and to consider which of them should be printed, and he was finally entrusted with the preparation of the work. It was published by Robert Waldegrave on 15 May 1597, under the title \u2018The Lawes and Actes of Parliament maid be King James the First and his successors kings of Scotland, visied, coffected, and extracted forth of the Register,\u2019 and on 3 June the privy council remitted to the lords of session to enforce the purchase of it by all subjects of sufficient \u2018substance and habilitie\u2019.\"<ref>Dictionary of National Biography, v. 52, p. 337.</ref>\n\nIn 1604 he bought the lands of Curriehill Castle. Curriehill is north of [[Currie]], a village to south of [[Edinburgh]].<ref>[https://canmore.org.uk/site/50268/curriehill-castle HES/RCAHMS Canmore: Curriehill Castle].</ref> He took \"Lord Curriehill\" as his title.\n\nHe is buried in [[Greyfriars Kirkyard]] in [[Edinburgh]]. His memorial stands on the north face of the church.\n\n==Ane Account of ane Embassie, 1590==\nJohn Skene's wrote an account of his embassy to Denmark in 1590, known from a copy made by the antiquary [[Robert Mylne (writer)|Robert Mylne]]. This is in the form of a journal of events.<ref>David Scott Gehring, ''Diplomatic Intelligence on the Holy Roman Empire and Denmark during the Reigns of Elizabeth I and James VI'', Camden Fifth Series, 49 (2016), pp. 18-20, 39-42, 44-45, 46-48.</ref> Skene left Edinburgh with William Stewart on 9 June 1590 and rode to [[Berwick upon Tweed]] and on to London. Their secretary John Geddie spoke to [[William Cecil, 1st Baron Burghley|William Cecil]] to arrange an audience with [[Elizabeth I of England]] at [[Greenwich Palace]]. On 17 June they came to court again and spoke to [[Christopher Hatton]] the Chancellor, the Treasurer (Cecil), the [[Charles Howard, 1st Earl of Nottingham|Admiral]], [[William Brooke, 10th Baron Cobham|Lord Cobham]], and [[Thomas Sackville, 1st Earl of Dorset|Lord Buckhurst]]. They also spoke to the French ambassador Jean de la Fin, Sieur de Beavoir la Nocle. They embarked on the ''George Noble'' at [[Leigh on Sea]], and after some difficulty sailed to [[Heligoland]] and [[Stade]], then crossed the [[Elbe]] into [[Holstein]].<ref>David Scott Gehring, ''Diplomatic Intelligence on the Holy Roman Empire and Denmark during the Reigns of Elizabeth I and James VI'', Camden Fifth Series, 49 (2016), pp. 151-154.</ref>\n\nOn his return, in London, they stayed at an inn on [[Gracechurch Street]]. Skene got an appointment with William Cecil, who received him lying on his bed at [[Cecil House]], because he was old and weary. Skene told him details of his negotiations in Denmark, Germany, and the Low Countries. The next day he went with Cecil to [[Somerset House]] and waited in the Chamber of Presence until the queen came out at 11 o'clock on her way to [[Richmond Palace]]. Skene then went to [[York House, Strand|York House]] in Westminster and met the French ambassadors Beauvais and [[Henri de La Tour d'Auvergne, Duke of Bouillon|Henri de la Tour, Viscount of Turenne]].<ref>David Scott Gehring, ''Diplomatic Intelligence on the Holy Roman Empire and Denmark during the Reigns of Elizabeth I and James VI'', Camden Fifth Series, 49 (2016), pp. 211-215.</ref>\n\n==Family==\nHe was married to Helen Somerville of [[Cambusnethan]]. Their children included;\n* Catherine Skene, who married [[Alexander Hay, Lord Fosterseat]].\n* Jane Skene, who married Sir William Scott of Ardross, their daughter Euphemia Scott married [[William Cochrane, 1st Earl of Dundonald|William Cochrane]] and was Countess of Dundonald.\n* Euphemia Skene, married Sir Robert Richardson of [[Pencaitland]].<ref>''The Staggering State of the Scots Statesman'', Sir John Scot.</ref>\n* Margaret Skene, married Robert Learmonth, brother of the Laird of Balcomie, Fife.\n* [[James Skene, Lord Curriehill]] (d. 15 October 1633), who married Janet Johnston.\n* John Skene of Halyards, \n* Alexander Skene, who married Joneta Syms. Their son John Skene was Keeper of the [[Letters of horning|Register of Hornings]].<ref>William Forbes Skene, ''Memorials of the family of Skene of Skene'' (Aberdeen, 1887), p. 112.</ref>\n* William Skene.\n\n==Sources==\n* Concise Dictionary of National Biography\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite DNB|wstitle=Skene, John}}\n* [https://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/history/ssne/item.php?id=1585 'SKENE, SIR JOHN (SSNE 1585)', St Andrew University, The Scotland, Scandinavia and Northern European Biographical Database].\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skene, John Lord Curriehill}}\n[[Category:1549 births]]\n[[Category:1617 deaths|Skene, John]]\n[[Category:Senators of the College of Justice|Currehill]]\n[[Category:Members of the Faculty of Advocates|Skene, John]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Scottish legal writers]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of St Andrews]]\n[[Category:Lord Advocates]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|Deputy Governor of the West Jersey colony|John Skene (New Jersey)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n'''Sir John Skene, Lord Curriehill''' (1549&ndash;1617) was a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] prosecutor, ambassador, and judge. He was involved in the negotiations for the marriage of James VI and Anne of Denmark.\n[[File:The grave of John Skene, Lord Curriehill, Greyfriars Kirkyard, Edinburgh.jpg|thumb|300px|The grave of John Skene, Lord Curriehill, Greyfriars Kirkyard, Edinburgh]]\nHe was regent in [[St Mary's College, St Andrews]] from 1564-5 and became an [[Faculty of Advocates|advocate]] in 1575.\n\n==Life==\nHe was born in 1549. He was the sixth son of James Skene of Wester Corse (b.1505) and Janet Lumsden.<ref>https://www.clanmacfarlanegenealogy.info/genealogy/TNGWebsite/getperson.php?personID=I36978&tree=CC</ref> Their lands were at Bandodle or Wester Corse, a manor in Aberdeenshire.<ref>[https://canmore.org.uk/site/76536/wester-corse HES/RCAHMS Canmore: Wester Corse].</ref>\n\nIn his own writings he mentions his travels, describing the appearance of a travelling salesman in [[Krak\u00f3w]] in 1569. The writer [[Thomas Dempster]] mentions Skene's travels in the countries of Northern Europe and his fluency in their languages. [[James Melville of Halhill]] said he could give long speeches in Latin, and was \"good, true, and stout\".<ref>[https://archive.org/details/memorialsoffamil00sken/page/106 William Forbes Skene, ''Memorials of the family of Skene of Skene'' (Aberdeen, 1887), pp. 107-8].</ref>\n\nSkene enrolled or matriculated at the [[University of Wittenberg]] on 16 March 1570.<ref>David Scott Gehring, ''Diplomatic Intelligence on the Holy Roman Empire and Denmark during the Reigns of Elizabeth I and James VI'', Camden Fifth Series, 49 (2016), p. 156 fn. 32.</ref>\n\nSkene's career was advanced by the marriages of his sisters to [[Alexander Hay, Lord Fosterseat|Alexander Hay]], [[Lord Clerk Register]], and [[Walter Stewart, 1st Lord Blantyre|Lord Blantyre]], an exchequer official and one of the [[Octavians]].<ref>[https://archive.org/details/memorialsoffamil00sken/page/106 William Forbes Skene, ''Memorials of the family of Skene of Skene'' (Aberdeen, 1887), p. 106].</ref>\n\nAs joint [[Lord Advocate]] from 1589 to 1594, he was zealous in the [[Witch trials in early modern Scotland|prosecution of witches]]. He was appointed [[Lord Clerk Register]] and [[Court of Session|Lord of Session]], with the judicial title of Lord Curriehill in 1594, serving until 1611.\n\nAs a diplomat, Skene went to Denmark to seek an agreement over rights to [[Orkney]], and presented a memorandum on that topic to [[Sophie of Mecklenburg-G\u00fcstrow]] and the four regents of [[Christian IV of Denmark]] at [[Helsing\u00f8r]] on 20 August 1589. He was also given instructions to negotiate the terms of the royal marriage.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/calendarofmanusc03grea_1/page/420 ''Calendar of the manuscripts of the Most Honourable the Marquess of Salisbury preserved at Hatfield House'', vol. 3 (London, 1892), pp. 420-3].</ref> His companions were; [[George Keith, 5th Earl Marischal]], [[Andrew Keith, Lord Dingwall|Andrew Keith]], James Scrimgeour of [[Dudhope Castle|Dudhope]] the Constable of [[River Tay|Tay]] and standard bearer of Scotland, and [[George Young (diplomat)|George Young]].<ref>William Forbes Skene, ''Memorials of the family of Skene of Skene'' (Aberdeen, 1887), p. 109: ''Register of the Privy Council of Scotland'', vol. 4 (Edinburgh, 1881), pp. 822-4.</ref> He returned on to Scotland 23 July 1589 with his colleagues Andrew Keith, and George Young and went to [[James VI of Scotland]] at [[Boyne Castle]]. An English observer [[Thomas Fowler (courtier)|Thomas Fowler]] reported their news including the Danish opinion that James VI asked for too high a dowry, but they had seen extensive preparations for the marriage including a coach made of silver. According to their report, Anne of Denmark was keen for the marriage to go ahead, and Fowler wrote; \"the young lady is so far in love with the king's majesty as it were death to her to have it broken off, and has made good proof (in) diverse ways of her affection, which his majesty is apt enough to requite\".<ref>''Calendar of State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 124-7, quotation (modernised) p. 124, source [[British Library]] Egerton MS 2,598/16.</ref>\n\nOn 22 October 1589, he accompanied James VI on his voyage from Leith to Norway and Denmark to meet his wife [[Anne of Denmark]], and attended the meeting of the [[Privy Council of Scotland]] at Oslo on 25 November.<ref>''Register of the Privy Council of Scotland'', vol. 4 (Edinburgh, 1881), pp. 430, 438.</ref>\n\nJames VI had given Anne of Denmark a \"[[morning gift]]\" of lands and palaces. In the week before her coronation in Scotland the Danish ambassadors travelled to view these places and take formal possession. On 12 May 1589 the envoys were welcomed at [[Falkland Palace]] by the keeper, James Beaton of Creich. Skene produced a printed charter of the queen's lands in [[Fife, Scotland|Fife]] and as a traditional symbol of the transfer of ownership ([[sasine]]), the [[Admiral of the Realm|Danish Admiral]] [[Peder Munk]] was given a handful of earth. After this ceremony, the party rode to the Newhouse of [[Lochleven Castle]] to stay the night, then repeated the ritual at [[Dunfermline Palace]], and on 14 May at [[Linlithgow Palace]].<ref>David Stevenson, ''Scotland's Last Royal Wedding'' (John Donald: Edinburgh, 1997), pp. 102-3.</ref>\n\nIn June 1590 [[James VI of Scotland]] sent Skene and [[William Stewart of Houston|Colonel William Stewart]], [[Prior of May (Pittenweem)|Commendator of Pittenweem]], as ambassadors to Denmark and Germany.<ref>David Scott Gehring, \u2018ANE ACCOUNT OF ANE EMBASSIE\u2019, 1590' in ''Diplomatic Intelligence on the Holy Roman Empire and Denmark during the Reigns of Elizabeth I and James VI'', Camden Fifth Series, 49 (2016), pp. 151-217.</ref> The mission was to intended to cement a peaceful league in Europe.<ref>Thomas Rymer, ''Foedera'', vol. 16 (London, 1715), pp. 68-71: Annie I. Cameron, ''Warrender Papers'', vol. 2 (Edinburgh, 1932), pp. 133-41.</ref> They met the mother of [[Anne of Denmark]], [[Sophie of Mecklenburg-G\u00fcstrow]] at [[Braunschweig]], then went on to meet [[William IV, Landgrave of Hesse-Kassel]] at [[Rotenburg an der Fulda]] and [[Christian I, Elector of Saxony]] at Dresden. Skene was ill when he returned to Edinburgh.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 12 (Edinburgh, 1952), pp. 370, 384, 388, 492.</ref>\n\nHe served as ambassador to Holland from 1591.\n\nHis compilation of old Scots law ''[[Regiam Majestatem]]'' is a source of the laws of Scotland previous to [[James I of Scotland|James I]]. He was granted a pension by [[James Douglas, 4th Earl of Morton|Regent Morton]] for preparing a digest of laws. He also produced a [[Scots law]] dictionary, ''De Verborum Significatione''. According to the Dictionary of National Biography, \"In 1592 he was named one of a commission to examine the laws and acts of parliament, and to consider which of them should be printed, and he was finally entrusted with the preparation of the work. It was published by Robert Waldegrave on 15 May 1597, under the title \u2018The Lawes and Actes of Parliament maid be King James the First and his successors kings of Scotland, visied, coffected, and extracted forth of the Register,\u2019 and on 3 June the privy council remitted to the lords of session to enforce the purchase of it by all subjects of sufficient \u2018substance and habilitie\u2019.\"<ref>Dictionary of National Biography, v. 52, p. 337.</ref> \n\nIn 1604 he bought the lands of Curriehill Castle. Curriehill is north of [[Currie]], a village to south of [[Edinburgh]].<ref>[https://canmore.org.uk/site/50268/curriehill-castle HES/RCAHMS Canmore: Curriehill Castle].</ref> He took \"Lord Curriehill\" as his title.\n\nHe is buried in [[Greyfriars Kirkyard]] in [[Edinburgh]]. His memorial stands on the north face of the church.\n\n==Ane Account of ane Embassie, 1590==\nJohn Skene's wrote an account of his embassy to Denmark in 1590, known from a copy made by the antiquary [[Robert Mylne (writer)|Robert Mylne]]. This is in the form of a journal of events.<ref>David Scott Gehring, ''Diplomatic Intelligence on the Holy Roman Empire and Denmark during the Reigns of Elizabeth I and James VI'', Camden Fifth Series, 49 (2016), pp. 18-20, 39-42, 44-45, 46-48.</ref> Skene left Edinburgh with William Stewart on 9 June 1590 and rode to [[Berwick upon Tweed]] and on to London. Their secretary John Geddie spoke to [[William Cecil, 1st Baron Burghley|William Cecil]] to arrange an audience with [[Elizabeth I of England]] at [[Greenwich Palace]]. On 17 June they came to court again and spoke to [[Christopher Hatton]] the Chancellor, the Treasurer (Cecil), the [[Charles Howard, 1st Earl of Nottingham|Admiral]], [[William Brooke, 10th Baron Cobham|Lord Cobham]], and [[Thomas Sackville, 1st Earl of Dorset|Lord Buckhurst]]. They also spoke to the French ambassador Jean de la Fin, Sieur de Beavoir la Nocle. They embarked on the ''George Noble'' at [[Leigh on Sea]], and after some difficulty sailed to [[Heligoland]] and [[Stade]], then crossed the [[Elbe]] into [[Holstein]].<ref>David Scott Gehring, ''Diplomatic Intelligence on the Holy Roman Empire and Denmark during the Reigns of Elizabeth I and James VI'', Camden Fifth Series, 49 (2016), pp. 151-154.</ref>\n\nOn his return, in London, they stayed at an inn on [[Gracechurch Street]]. Skene got an appointment with William Cecil, who received him lying on his bed at [[Cecil House]], because he was old and weary. Skene told him details of his negotiations in Denmark, Germany, and the Low Countries. The next day he went with Cecil to [[Somerset House]] and waited in the Chamber of Presence until the queen came out at 11 o'clock on her way to [[Richmond Palace]]. Skene then went to [[York House, Strand|York House]] in Westminster and met the French ambassadors Beauvais and [[Henri de La Tour d'Auvergne, Duke of Bouillon|Henri de la Tour, Viscount of Turenne]].<ref>David Scott Gehring, ''Diplomatic Intelligence on the Holy Roman Empire and Denmark during the Reigns of Elizabeth I and James VI'', Camden Fifth Series, 49 (2016), pp. 211-215.</ref>\n\n==Family==\nHe was married to Helen Somerville of [[Cambusnethan]]. Their children included;\n* Catherine Skene, who married [[Alexander Hay, Lord Fosterseat]].\n* Jane Skene, who married Sir William Scott of Ardross, their daughter Euphemia Scott married [[William Cochrane, 1st Earl of Dundonald|William Cochrane]] and was Countess of Dundonald.\n* Euphemia Skene, married Sir Robert Richardson of [[Pencaitland]].<ref>''The Staggering State of the Scots Statesman'', Sir John Scot.</ref>\n* Margaret Skene, married Robert Learmonth, brother of the Laird of Balcomie, Fife.\n* [[James Skene, Lord Curriehill]] (d. 15 October 1633), who married Janet Johnston.\n* John Skene of Halyards, \n* Alexander Skene, who married Joneta Syms. Their son John Skene was Keeper of the [[Letters of horning|Register of Hornings]].<ref>William Forbes Skene, ''Memorials of the family of Skene of Skene'' (Aberdeen, 1887), p. 112.</ref>\n* William Skene.\n\n==Sources==\n* Concise Dictionary of National Biography\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite DNB|wstitle=Skene, John}}\n* [https://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/history/ssne/item.php?id=1585 'SKENE, SIR JOHN (SSNE 1585)', St Andrew University, The Scotland, Scandinavia and Northern European Biographical Database].\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skene, John Lord Curriehill}}\n[[Category:1549 births]]\n[[Category:1617 deaths|Skene, John]]\n[[Category:Senators of the College of Justice|Currehill]]\n[[Category:Members of the Faculty of Advocates|Skene, John]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Scottish legal writers]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of St Andrews]]\n[[Category:Lord Advocates]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-law-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, removed stub tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Skene,_Lord_Curriehill"}
