tegory:People from Manhattan]]\n[[Category:People stripped of honorary degrees]]\n[[Category:Politicians from New York City]]\n[[Category:Presbyterians from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the United States]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Abdulaziz al Saud]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Presidential Order of Excellence]]\n[[Category:Reform Party of the United States of America politicians]]\n[[Category:Republican Party (United States) presidential nominees]]\n[[Category:Republican Party Presidents of the United States]]\n[[Category:Right-wing populism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Television producers from New York City]]\n[[Category:The Trump Organization employees]]\n[[Category:Trump family|Donald]]\n[[Category:United States Football League executives]]\n[[Category:WWE Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n", "name_user": "Mandruss", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2020 presidential campaign:cite cleanup", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donald_Trump"}
{"title_page": "Guillaume Delcourt", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Delcourt}}{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = [[Belgian military ranks|Lieutenant at sea, 1st class  ]]\n| name          = Guillaume Delcourt\n| honorific_suffix = [[Military Cross (Belgium)|Military Cross]], [[Order of Leopold (Belgium)|Off. O. Leopold]], [[Order of Christ (Portugal)|ComC]]\n| image         = File:Crop Guillaume Delcourt Portrait.png\n| caption       = Portrait of Delcourt by Louis-Joseph Gh\u00e9mar (lithography, 1854)\n| birth_date    = 31 March 1825\n| death_date    = 2 February 1898 (at 72)\n| birth_place   = [[Brussels]]\n| death_place   = [[Antwerp]]\n| birth_name    = Guillaume-Louis Delcourt\n| allegiance    = {{Flag|Kingdom of Belgium}}\n| branch        = [[File:Naval Ensign of Belgium.svg|22px]] [[Belgian Navy]]\n| rank          = [[File:Generic-Navy-O4.svg|22px]] [[Belgian military ranks|Lieutenant at sea, 1st class  ]]\n| battles       = [[Rio Nunez incident|Battle of Rio Nunez]]\n| awards        = Officer of the [[Order of Leopold (Belgium)|Order of Leopold]], [[Military Cross (Belgium)|Military Cross]], Commander of the [[Order of Christ (Portugal)]]\n| alma_mater    = [[File:Blason ERM.svg|22px]] [[Royal Military Academy (Belgium)|Royal Military Academy]]<br>\u00c9cole Nationale Sup\u00e9rieure du G\u00e9nie Maritime ([[ENSTA Paris]])\n| spouse        = Laurence Hortense Jos\u00e9phine Lambrechts (b. 1832)\n| relations     = Lambrechts family, [[Wittouck family]], [[Van Dievoet family]]\n}}\n\n'''Guillaume Delcourt''' (31 March 1825 \u2013 2 February 1898) was a [[Belgian Navy|Belgian Royal Navy]] officer, [[navigator]], [[naval engineer]], and maritime advisor to [[Leopold II of Belgium|King Leopold II]]. He was one of the major players in [[Belgian colonial empire|Belgian expansion]] around the world.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Early years and family ===\nGuillaume Delcourt's parents died young, leaving him an orphan as a child. His mother was [[Wittouck family|Barbara Wittouck]] (died in Brussels on 17 June 1830), daughter of the jurisconsult [[Guillaume Wittouck]], whom Delcourt was named after. His father Napoleon Joseph Delcourt, a brewer born in [[Ath]], was injured while fighting for the [[Belgian Revolution]] in 1830<ref>Auguste de Wargny, ''Suppl\u00e9ment aux esquisses historiques de la premi\u00e8re \u00e9poque de la R\u00e9volution de la Belgique en 1830. Du 25 ao\u00fbt au 29 septembre \u2013 espace de 35 jours'', Brussels, published by J.-P. Meline, libraire-\u00e9diteur, 1831, p. 29.</ref> and died three years later in Antwerp on 30 July 1833. After the death of his parents he was raised by his mother's sister, Jeanette Wittouck and her husband [[Van Dievoet family|Jean-Louis Van Dievoet]], [[Secretary (title)|secretary]] of the [[Court of Cassation (Belgium)|Belgian Supreme Court]].\n\n=== Education ===\nAfter a brief career in banking, Delcourt was admitted at the [[Royal Military Academy (Belgium)|Royal Military Academy]] in 1842 as an [[officer candidate]] of 2<sup>nd</sup> class. He graduated after 2 years as an officer candidate of 1<sup>st</sup> class.\n\n=== Career ===\nStarting in, 1845 he sailed on the ''Macassar'' on board which he had to face numerous challenges in the [[China Seas]]: typhoons, storms, grounding, etc.. He then sailed for [[Batavia, Dutch East Indies|Batavia]]. While in route for [[Singapore]] in 1847, his ship was attacked by pirates in the [[Riau Archipelago|Riau straight]]. On his way back it was almost shipwrecked. [[File:La prise de Debokk\u00e9.jpg|thumb|Belgian and French warships during the [[Rio Nu\u00f1ez incident|Rio Nu\u00f1ez Incident]] by [[Paul Jean Clays]]|304x304px]]Delcourt, then aboard the ''Louise Marie'', sails for the [[Rio Nunez]], where [[Leopold I of Belgium|Leopold I]] had created a colony, and arrived there on 10 February 1849. He participated in the [[Rio Nu\u00f1ez incident]] on 23 March 1849. During his return, his ship silted up and found itself in a bad position, taking shots from partisans of Mayor\u00e9, but was saved by the Africans that stayed loyal to the Belgians.<ref>Ch. Maroy, ''La colonie belge du Rio Nunez et l'exp\u00e9dition franco-belge de Boki\u00e9 en 1849'', in: Bulletin d'\u00c9tudes et d'Informations de l'\u00c9cole sup\u00e9rieure du Commerce, Antwerp, September-October, 1930.</ref><ref>A. Demougeot, ''Histoire du Nunez'', in: Bulletin du Comit\u00e9 d'\u00c9tudes Historiques et Scientifiques de l'A.O.F., Volume 21, No. 2, 1938, pp. 177-289 (Mainly chapter IV, ''Les Belges au Nunez''.)</ref> \n\nAfter this successful campaign, Leopold I promoted him to the [[Belgian military ranks|rank]] of [[Ensign (rank)|Ensign at sea]].  \n\nHe makes another trip in 1850 to the [[Rio Nunez]] but the situation had worsened. He then leaves for the Belgian colony of [[Santo Tom\u00e1s de Castilla|Santo-Thomas]] in Guatemala that was also collapsing.<ref>Huguette De Clerck, ''Le cauchemar guat\u00e9malt\u00e8que: les Belges au Vera-Paz de 1842 \u00e0 1858'', s.l. s.n., 2002</ref>  \n\nIn 1851, he leaves once more on board the ''Louise-Marie'' to the Rio Nunez; while on the [[Gor\u00e9e|island of Gor\u00e9e]], the Belgians receive a message from the consul of Belgium L. Bols-Wittouck, a cousin of Delcourt, asking them to get back to Rio-Nunez rapidly as the situation was getting worse.  \n\nDelcourt was made [[Belgian military ranks|Lieutenant at sea, 1<sup>st</sup> class]] on 1 July 1863.<ref name=\":0\">A. Lederer, ''Guillaume Delcourt, conseiller maritime de Leopold II'', in : Biographie belge d\u2019Outremer, 1973, T. VII, col. 165-175. [https://www.kaowarsom.be/documents/BIOGRAPHIE%20COLONIALE%20BELGE%20-%20BELGISCHE%20KOLONIALE%20BIOGRAFIE/TOME%20VIIa/TOME%20VIIa.pdf Read online]</ref>   \n\nIn 1865, he was named engineer of maritime constructions, he helped develop the [[port of Antwerp]]. He became the maritime advisor of Leopold II and advised the king on the necessary maritime equipment for [[Henry Morton Stanley|Sir Henry Morton Stanley]] and his [[Congo Free State#Stanley's exploration|expedition]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== His writings ==\nHis many writings are kept at the [[Royal Museum of the Armed Forces and Military History]]. These include his [[Logbook|logbooks]] from his travels to [[Manila]], [[Indonesia]], and the West coast of Africa as well as his \"extremely interesting\" correspondence.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Honours ==\n\n==={{Flag|Belgium}}===\n\n* [[File:Officer_Ordre_de_Leopold.png|50x50px]] Officer of the [[Order of Leopold (Belgium)|Order of Leopold]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[File:BEL Militair Kruis 1klasse BAR.svg|50x50px]] [[Military Cross (Belgium)|Military Cross, 1<sup>st</sup> class]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==={{Flag|Portugal}}===\n\n* [[File:PRT_Order_of_Christ_-_Commander_BAR.png|50x50px]] Commander of the [[Order of Christ (Portugal)|Order of Christ]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Wittouck family]]\n\n=== External links ===\n\n* [https://www.kaowarsom.be/documents/BIOGRAPHIE%20COLONIALE%20BELGE%20-%20BELGISCHE%20KOLONIALE%20BIOGRAFIE/TOME%20VIIa/TOME%20VIIa.pdf Biography] (in French) on the website of the [[Royal Academy for Overseas Sciences]]\n*[http://www.marinebelge.be/louise-marie%201.html Passage from his logbook : \"La c\u00f4te d'Afrique 1848-1849 par Delcourt\"] (in French) at the bottom of the page\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* Ch. Maroy, ''La colonie belge du Rio Nunez et l'exp\u00e9dition franco-belge de Boki\u00e9 en 1849'', in: Bulletin d'\u00c9tudes et d'Informations de l'\u00c9cole sup\u00e9rieure du Commerce, Antwerp, September-October, 1930.\n* A. Demougeot, ''Histoire du Nunez'', in: Bulletin du Comit\u00e9 d'\u00c9tudes Historiques et Scientifiques de l'A.O.F., Volume 21, No. 2, 1938, pp. 177-289 (Mainly chapter IV, ''Les Belges au Nunez''.)\n* J.-B. Leconte, ''Les tentatives d'expansion coloniale sous le r\u00e8gne de Leopold Ier'', Antwerp, 1946.\n* L. Leconte, ''Les anc\u00eatres de notre Force navale'', Brussels, 1952.\n* A. Lederer, ''Histoire de la navigation au Congo'', Tervuren, 1965.\n* R. Massinon, ''L'entreprise du Rio-Nunez'', in: Acad\u00e9mie Royale des Sciences d'Outre-Mer, Bulletin des S\u00e9ances, Brussels, 1965, pp. 304\u2013353\n* Acad\u00e9mie royale des sciences d'outremer, ''L'expansion belge sous L\u00e9opold Ier, 1831-1865'', Brussels, 1965.\n* A. Lederer, ''Guillaume Delcourt, conseiller maritime de Leopold II'', in : Biographie belge d\u2019Outremer, 1973, T. VII, col. 165-175.\n* Huguette De Clerck, ''Le cauchemar guat\u00e9malt\u00e8que: les Belges au Vera-Paz de 1842 \u00e0 1858'', s.l. s.n., 2002\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Delcourt}}\n[[Category:1825 births]]\n[[Category:1898 deaths]]\n[[Category:Navy officers]]\n[[Category:Belgian people]]\n[[Category:Belgian Navy]]\n[[Category:Belgian military personnel]]\n[[Category:Navigators]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Delcourt}}{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = [[Belgian military ranks|Lieutenant at sea, 1st class  ]]\n| name          = Guillaume Delcourt\n| honorific_suffix = [[Military Cross (Belgium)|Military Cross]], [[Order of Leopold (Belgium)|Off. O. Leopold]], [[Order of Christ (Portugal)|ComC]]\n| image         = File:Crop Guillaume Delcourt Portrait.png\n| caption       = Portrait of Delcourt by Louis-Joseph Gh\u00e9mar (lithography, 1854)\n| birth_date    = 31 March 1825\n| death_date    = 2 February 1898 (at 72)\n| birth_place   = [[Brussels]]\n| death_place   = [[Antwerp]]\n| birth_name    = Guillaume-Louis Delcourt\n| allegiance    = {{Flag|Kingdom of Belgium}}\n| branch        = [[File:Naval Ensign of Belgium.svg|22px]] [[Belgian Navy]]\n| rank          = [[File:Generic-Navy-O4.svg|22px]] [[Belgian military ranks|Lieutenant at sea, 1st class  ]]\n| battles       = [[Rio Nunez incident|Battle of Rio Nunez]]\n| awards        = Officer of the [[Order of Leopold (Belgium)|Order of Leopold]], [[Military Cross (Belgium)|Military Cross]], Commander of the [[Order of Christ (Portugal)]]\n| alma_mater    = [[File:Blason ERM.svg|22px]] [[Royal Military Academy (Belgium)|Royal Military Academy]]<br>\u00c9cole Nationale Sup\u00e9rieure du G\u00e9nie Maritime ([[ENSTA Paris]])\n| spouse        = Laurence Hortense Jos\u00e9phine Lambrechts (b. 1832)\n| relations     = Lambrechts family, [[Wittouck family]], [[Van Dievoet family]]\n}}\n\n'''Guillaume Delcourt''' (31 March 1825 \u2013 2 February 1898) was a [[Belgian Navy|Belgian Royal Navy]] officer, [[navigator]], [[naval engineer]], and maritime advisor to [[Leopold II of Belgium|King Leopold II]]. He was one of the major players in [[Belgian colonial empire|Belgian expansion]] around the world.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Early years and family ===\nGuillaume Delcourt's parents died young, leaving him an orphan as a child. His mother was [[Wittouck family|Barbara Wittouck]] (died in Brussels on 17 June 1830), daughter of the jurisconsult [[Guillaume Wittouck]], whom Delcourt was named after. His father Napoleon Joseph Delcourt, a brewer born in [[Ath]], was injured while fighting for the [[Belgian Revolution]] in 1830<ref>Auguste de Wargny, ''Suppl\u00e9ment aux esquisses historiques de la premi\u00e8re \u00e9poque de la R\u00e9volution de la Belgique en 1830. Du 25 ao\u00fbt au 29 septembre \u2013 espace de 35 jours'', Brussels, published by J.-P. Meline, libraire-\u00e9diteur, 1831, p. 29.</ref> and died three years later in Antwerp on 30 July 1833. After the death of his parents he was raised by his mother's sister, Jeanette Wittouck and her husband [[Van Dievoet family|Jean-Louis Van Dievoet]], [[Secretary (title)|secretary]] of the [[Court of Cassation (Belgium)|Belgian Supreme Court]].\n\n=== Education ===\nAfter a brief career in banking, Delcourt was admitted at the [[Royal Military Academy (Belgium)|Royal Military Academy]] in 1842 as an [[officer candidate]] of 2<sup>nd</sup> class. He graduated after 2 years as an officer candidate of 1<sup>st</sup> class.\n\n=== Career ===\nStarting in, 1845 he sailed on the ''Macassar'' on board which he had to face numerous challenges in the [[China Seas]]: typhoons, storms, grounding, etc.. He then sailed for [[Batavia, Dutch East Indies|Batavia]]. While in route for [[Singapore]] in 1847, his ship was attacked by pirates in the [[Riau Archipelago|Riau straight]]. On his way back it was almost shipwrecked. [[File:La prise de Debokk\u00e9.jpg|thumb|Belgian and French warships during the [[Rio Nu\u00f1ez incident|Rio Nu\u00f1ez Incident]] by [[Paul Jean Clays]]|304x304px]]Delcourt, then aboard the ''Louise Marie'', sails for the [[Rio Nunez]], where [[Leopold I of Belgium|Leopold I]] had created a colony, and arrived there on 10 February 1849. He participated in the [[Rio Nu\u00f1ez incident]] on 23 March 1849. During his return, his ship silted up and found itself in a bad position, taking shots from partisans of Mayor\u00e9, but was saved by the Africans that stayed loyal to the Belgians.<ref>Ch. Maroy, ''La colonie belge du Rio Nunez et l'exp\u00e9dition franco-belge de Boki\u00e9 en 1849'', in: Bulletin d'\u00c9tudes et d'Informations de l'\u00c9cole sup\u00e9rieure du Commerce, Antwerp, September-October, 1930.</ref><ref>A. Demougeot, ''Histoire du Nunez'', in: Bulletin du Comit\u00e9 d'\u00c9tudes Historiques et Scientifiques de l'A.O.F., Volume 21, No. 2, 1938, pp. 177-289 (Mainly chapter IV, ''Les Belges au Nunez''.)</ref> \n\nAfter this successful campaign, Leopold I promoted him to the [[Belgian military ranks|rank]] of [[Ensign (rank)|Ensign at sea]].  \n\nHe makes another trip in 1850 to the [[Rio Nunez]] but the situation had worsened. He then leaves for the Belgian colony of [[Santo Tom\u00e1s de Castilla|Santo-Thomas]] in Guatemala that was also collapsing.<ref>Huguette De Clerck, ''Le cauchemar guat\u00e9malt\u00e8que: les Belges au Vera-Paz de 1842 \u00e0 1858'', s.l. s.n., 2002</ref>  \n\nIn 1851, he leaves once more on