E%20VIIa.pdf Biography] (in French) on the website of the [[Royal Academy for Overseas Sciences]]\n*[http://www.marinebelge.be/louise-marie%201.html Passage from his logbook : \"La c\u00f4te d'Afrique 1848-1849 par Delcourt\"] (in French) at the bottom of the page\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* Ch. Maroy, ''La colonie belge du Rio Nunez et l'exp\u00e9dition franco-belge de Boki\u00e9 en 1849'', in: Bulletin d'\u00c9tudes et d'Informations de l'\u00c9cole sup\u00e9rieure du Commerce, Antwerp, September-October, 1930.\n* A. Demougeot, ''Histoire du Nunez'', in: Bulletin du Comit\u00e9 d'\u00c9tudes Historiques et Scientifiques de l'A.O.F., Volume 21, No. 2, 1938, pp. 177-289 (Mainly chapter IV, ''Les Belges au Nunez''.)\n* J.-B. Leconte, ''Les tentatives d'expansion coloniale sous le r\u00e8gne de Leopold Ier'', Antwerp, 1946.\n* L. Leconte, ''Les anc\u00eatres de notre Force navale'', Brussels, 1952.\n* A. Lederer, ''Histoire de la navigation au Congo'', Tervuren, 1965.\n* R. Massinon, ''L'entreprise du Rio-Nunez'', in: Acad\u00e9mie Royale des Sciences d'Outre-Mer, Bulletin des S\u00e9ances, Brussels, 1965, pp. 304\u2013353\n* Acad\u00e9mie royale des sciences d'outremer, ''L'expansion belge sous L\u00e9opold Ier, 1831-1865'', Brussels, 1965.\n* A. Lederer, ''Guillaume Delcourt, conseiller maritime de Leopold II'', in : Biographie belge d\u2019Outremer, 1973, T. VII, col. 165-175.\n* Huguette De Clerck, ''Le cauchemar guat\u00e9malt\u00e8que: les Belges au Vera-Paz de 1842 \u00e0 1858'', s.l. s.n., 2002\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Delcourt}}\n[[Category:1825 births]]\n[[Category:1898 deaths]]\n[[Category:Navy officers]]\n[[Category:Belgian people]]\n[[Category:Belgian Navy]]\n[[Category:Belgian military personnel]]\n[[Category:Navigators]]\n", "name_user": "Brookford", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guillaume_Delcourt"}
{"title_page": "Animal Crossing", "text_new": "{{short description|Video game series developed by Nintendo}}\n{{about|the video game series|the first game in the series|Animal Crossing (video game)|other uses|}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game series\n| width = 400\n| title = Animal Crossing\n| image = Animal_Crossing_Logo.png\n| caption = ''Animal Crossing'' series logo\n| genre = [[Social simulation game|Social simulation]]\n| creator = [[Katsuya Eguchi]]\n| developer = {{Unbulleted list|[[Nintendo EAD]]|[[Nintendo Entertainment Planning & Development|Nintendo EPD]]|[[NDcube]]}}\n| publisher = [[Nintendo]]\n| platforms = {{Hlist|[[Nintendo 64]]|[[iQue Player]]|[[GameCube]]|[[Wii]]|[[Wii U]]|[[Nintendo DS]]|[[Nintendo 3DS]]|[[iOS]]|[[Android (operating system)|Android]]|[[Nintendo Switch]]}}\n| first release version = ''[[Animal Crossing (video game)|Animal Crossing]]''\n| first release date = April 14, 2001\n| latest release version = ''[[Animal Crossing: New Horizons]]''\n| latest release date = March 20, 2020\n| spinoffs = {{Unbulleted list|''[[Happy Home Designer]]''|''[[Amiibo Festival]]''|''[[Pocket Camp]]''}}\n}}\n\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Animal Crossing'''''|\u3069\u3046\u3076\u3064\u306e\u68ee|D\u014dbutsu no Mori|''Animal Forest''|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a [[social simulation game|social simulation]] [[video game]] series developed and published by [[Nintendo]] and created by [[Katsuya Eguchi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.droidgamers.com/index.php/apps/7395-while-animal-crossing-may-never-see-a-mobile-game-there-could-be-companion-apps-on-the-way|title=While Animal Crossing may never see a mobile game, there could be companion apps on the way|author=Andrew H|website=droidgamers.com|date=March 27, 2014|accessdate=February 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304072130/http://www.droidgamers.com/index.php/apps/7395-while-animal-crossing-may-never-see-a-mobile-game-there-could-be-companion-apps-on-the-way|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/no-retro-games-in-future-animal-crossings-with-one-poss-512085493|title=No Retro Games in Future Animal Crossings\u2014With One Possible Exception|author=Stephen Totilo|website=kotaku.com|date=June 8, 2013|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/e3-08-nintendo-press-conference/|title=E3 08: Nintendo Press Conference|author=Brett Elston|website=gamesradar.com|date=July 15, 2008|accessdate=February 24, 2016}}</ref> In ''Animal Crossing'', the [[player character]] is a human who lives in a village inhabited by various [[Anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]] animals, carrying out various activities such as fishing, bug catching, and fossil hunting. The series is notable for its [[Nonlinear gameplay|open-ended]] gameplay and extensive use of the [[video game console]]'s internal clock and calendar to simulate [[Real time (media)|real passage of time]].\n\nSince its [[Animal Crossing (video game)|initial release]] in 2001, five ''Animal Crossing'' games have been released worldwide, one each for the [[Nintendo 64]]/[[iQue Player]] (enhanced and reissued for the [[GameCube]]), [[Nintendo DS]], [[Wii]], [[Nintendo 3DS]] and [[Nintendo Switch]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techradar.com/news/animal-crossing-on-nintendo-switch|title=Animal Crossing on Nintendo Switch: release date, news and features|last=Hood|first=Vic|last2=Gaming|first2=Nick Pino 2019-06-18T17:06:19Z|website=TechRadar|language=en|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref> The series has been both critically and commercially successful and has sold over 30 million units worldwide. Three spin-off games have also been released: ''[[Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer]]'' for [[Nintendo 3DS]], ''[[Animal Crossing: Amiibo Festival]]'' for [[Wii U]], and ''[[Animal Crossing: Pocket Camp]]'' for mobile devices.\n\n== Common elements ==\n\n=== Characters ===\nWhile the series features various villagers for each title, certain prominent characters return in each series installment. [[Tom Nook]] is a [[Japanese raccoon dog|tanuki]] character who functions as both a shop owner and real estate broker, giving the player a loan for their house and allowing them to pay it back with no interest. He is one of the only residents of the town to follow a [[Capitalism|capitalist]] ethos. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/tom-nook-needs-to-get-with-the-times-1829149177|title=Tom Nook Needs To Get With The Times|last=Jackson|first=Gita|website=Kotaku|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> [[Mr. Resetti]] is a mole character who appears from underground whenever players shut off the game without saving, berating them for circumventing one of the game's systems. Due to a new [[autosave]] function, he was \"laid off\" from his job in ''Animal Crossing: New Horizons'', although he has gotten a new job as the Rescue Service operator. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2019/06/17/animal-crossing-new-horizons-autosave-resettis-job/|title=Animal Crossing New Horizons has autosave, so Resetti's out of a job|date=2019-06-17|website=VG247|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref>\n\n[[K.K. Slider]] is a canine traveling musician based on series composer [[Kazumi Totaka]], and plays on certain nights in the town's club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2013/05/profile_kazumi_totaka_the_man_behind_animal_crossings_kk_slider|title=Profile: Kazumi Totaka - The Man Behind Animal Crossing's K.K. Slider|last=Life|first=Nintendo|date=2013-05-08|website=Nintendo Life|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> Afterwards, he gifts the player a free copy of the song played, saying that his music \"wants to be free\". This was seen by some fans as tacit support for [[music piracy]], although Nintendo denied that it was intended as [[social commentary]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/19/technology/social-commentary-or-just-a-dogs-opinion.html|title=Social Commentary, or Just a Dog's Opinion?|last=Jr|first=Tom Zeller|date=2005-12-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-08-18|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===Gameplay===\nIn the ''Animal Crossing'' games, the player assumes the role of a human child, aged between 9-13, who moves into a rural village populated with anthropomorphic animals and lives there indefinitely. Gameplay is [[Nonlinear gameplay|open-ended]]: players have no defined objectives, but are instead encouraged to spend their time in the village performing any number of activities, which include collecting items, planting plants or other items, and socializing with the village's residents. Other villagers can also come to your island and chat with you! ''Animal Crossing'' games are played in [[Real time (media)|real time]], utilizing the [[video game console]]'s internal clock and calendar. Thus, passage of time in the game world reflects that in reality, as well as the current season and time of day. Some in-game events, such as holidays or the growth of a tree, occur at certain times or require some duration of time to have passed.<ref name=\"IGN_GC_preview\"/>\n\nOne notable feature of the ''Animal Crossing'' series is the high level of customization available, some of which affects the outcome of the game.<ref name=\"IGN_GC_review\" /> The [[player character]] is both named and gendered by the real life player at the start of the game, and their appearance can be modified by buying or designing custom clothes and accessories or changing the hairstyle (introduced in ''[[Animal Crossing: Wild World|Wild World]]''). The player's house can also be furnished, decorated, and later expanded: the player can purchase and collect furniture and place it anywhere in the house, as well as change both the wallpaper and floor designs. While its terrain, building locations, and initial residents are randomly generated when the game is first begun (except in ''Animal Crossing: New Leaf'', in which the player decides between four given towns, and ''Animal Crossing: New Horizons'', in which the player similarly decides between four given islands), the village's name and anthem, as well as some of the residents' catchphrases, are also determined by the player.<ref name=\"IGN_GC_review\"/>\n\nCollecting items is a major facet of ''Animal Crossing'': the player can explore the village and gather objects, including fruit from trees, seashells, and discarded items. Nearly all objects can be sold for Bells, the in-game currency. Players collect objects to obtain more Bells, which can then be used to buy furniture and clothing, purchase home expansions, invest in stocks, and play games. A number of specialized tools are available for other activities such as fishing and insect collecting. Special items, such as fossils and paintings, may be donated to the village museum. The player can choose to socialize with the other animal residents by engaging in conversation, sending and receiving letters, bartering, or playing hide-and-seek. Residents may move in or out of the village depending on the player's actions.\n\nAll installments of ''Animal Crossing'' allow some form of communication between players, both offline and [[Online game|online]]. A single village can house up to four human players, though only one can be exploring the village at any given time.<ref name=\"IGN_GC_preview\">{{cite web| title=Animal Crossing Preview |last=Schneider |first=Peer |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/05/30/animal-crossing |date=May 30, 2002 |publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> The players can interact via written messages through the village post office or bulletin board. The [[GameCube]] iteration allowed players to travel to other villages by trading [[Nintendo GameCube#Memory and storage|memory cards]] written with the game data,<ref name=\"IGN_GC_review\"/> but all subsequent installments allow players to travel and interact online via [[Nintendo Wi-Fi Connection]], although ''[[Animal Crossing: City Folk|City Folk]]'' also allows the DS Suitcase to travel to others' towns.<ref name=\"IGN_DS_review\"/><ref name=\"IGN_Wii_review\"/>\n\n==Games==\n\n{{Timeline of release years\n| summary = Timeline of releases in the ''Animal Crossing'' series, from 2001 to present.\n| range1       = 2001 \u2013\n| range1_color = #ffc836 #e5d2ac <!-- Based on series logo -->\n| 2001 = ''[[Animal Crossing (video game)|Animal Crossing]]''\n| 2005 = ''[[Animal Crossing: Wild World|Wild World]]''\n| 2008 = ''[[Animal Crossing: City Folk|City Folk]]''\n| 2012 = ''[[Animal Crossing: New Leaf|New Leaf]]''\n| 2015a = ''[[Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer|Happy Home Designer]]''\n| 2015b = ''[[Animal Crossing: Amiibo Festival|Amiibo Festival]]''\n| 2016 = ''[[Animal Crossing: New Leaf|New Leaf \u2013 Welcome Amiibo]]''\n| 2017 = ''[[Animal Crossing: Pocket Camp|Pocket Camp]]''\n| 2020 = ''[[Animal Crossing: New Horizons|New Horizons]]''\n}}\n\n===Main series===\n\n====''Animal Crossing'' (2001)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing (video game)}}\n''Animal Crossing''{{efn|Known in Japan as {{nihongo|''D\u014dbutsu no Mori''|\u3069\u3046\u3076\u3064\u306e\u68ee||lit. ''Animal Forest''}}}} originally released in Japan for the [[Nintendo 64]] in 2001. It was enhanced and released on the [[GameCube]] the same year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/11/13/the-evolution-of-animal-crossing-2?page=2 |title=The Evolution of Animal Crossing (page 2) |last=Harris |first=Craig |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> This version was localized and released in North America on September 16, 2002, Australia on October 17, 2003, and Europe on September 24, 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/games/action-replay-ultimate-codes-animal-crossing/gcn-16562 |title=Animal Crossing Review |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> An extended version titled \"D\u014dbutsu no Mori e+\" was released on June 27, 2003 in Japan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/games/doubutsu-no-mori/gcn-552545 |title=Doubutsu no Mori e+ |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> The Nintendo 64 version of the game was released in China in 2006 for [[iQue Player]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ique.com/games/21041.htm |title=Animal Forest |publisher=iQue Ltd. |language=Chinese |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====''Animal Crossing: Wild World'' (2005)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: Wild World}}\n''Animal Crossing: Wild World''{{efn|Known in Japan as {{nihongo|''Oideyo D\u014dbutsu no Mori''|\u304a\u3044\u3067\u3088 \u3069\u3046\u3076\u3064\u306e\u68ee||lit. ''Come to Animal Forest''}}}} was released for the [[Nintendo DS]] in Japan on November 23, 2005, North America on December 5, 2005, Australia on December 8, 2005, and Europe on March 31, 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/games/animal-crossing-wild-world/nds-682878 |title=Animal Crossing: Wild World Review |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> It was the first game in the series to use [[Nintendo Wi-Fi Connection]]. The game was later re-released on the [[Wii U]] [[Virtual Console]] on October 13, 2016, although its Wi-Fi multiplayer feature is unavailable due to the [[Nintendo Wi-Fi Connection#Closing|discontinuation]] of Nintendo Wi-Fi Connection.\n\n====''Animal Crossing: City Folk'' (2008)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: City Folk}}\n''Animal Crossing: City Folk'',{{efn|Known in Japan as {{nihongo|''Machi e Ik\u014d yo D\u014dbutsu no Mori''|\u8857\u3078\u884c\u3053\u3046\u3088 \u3069\u3046\u3076\u3064\u306e\u68ee||lit. ''Let's Go to the City: Animal Forest''}}}} known as ''Animal Crossing: Let's Go to the City'' in Europe and Australia, was released for the [[Wii]] in North America on November 16, 2008, Japan on November 20, 2008, Australia on December 4, 2008, and Europe on December 5, 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/games/animal-crossing-city-folk/wii-748892 |title=Animal Crossing: City Folk Review |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> It was later released in South Korea in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendo.co.kr/Wii/software/animal_crossing/main.php |title=\ud0c0\uc6b4\uc73c\ub85c \ub180\ub7ec\uac00\uc694 \ub3d9\ubb3c\uc758 \uc232 |publisher=Nintendo |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |language=Korean}}</ref> It was the first Wii game to utilize the [[Wii Speak]], an accessory that allows players to talk to each other during online play.\n\n====''Animal Crossing: New Leaf'' (2012)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: New Leaf}}\n''Animal Crossing: New Leaf''{{efn|Known in Japan as {{nihongo|''Tobidase D\u014dbutsu no Mori''|\u3068\u3073\u3060\u305b \u3069\u3046\u3076\u3064\u306e\u68ee||lit. ''Jump Out Animal Forest''}}}} was announced at [[E3 2010]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/06/15/e3-2010-animal-crossing-3ds-announced|title=E3 2010: Animal Crossing 3DS Announced|publisher=IGN|last=Thomas|first=Lucas M.|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> It was released for the [[Nintendo 3DS]] in Japan on November 8, 2012, North America on June 9, 2013, Europe on June 14, 2013, and Australia on June 15, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/games/animal-crossing-3ds/3ds-77803 |title=Animal Crossing: New Leaf |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> For the first time in the series, players are appointed to the role of Mayor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/10/25/animal-crossing-3ds-has-a-new-name|title=Animal Crossing 3DS Has a New Name|last=Drake|first=Audrey|publisher=IGN|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\nIn November 2016, a new update was released along with \"Welcome Amiibo\" in North America and Europe, adding several new locations, items and activities.<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome Amiibo|url=http://www.mojenintendo.cz/animal-crossing-new-leaf-welcome-amiibocard/|website=mojenintendo.cz|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====''Animal Crossing: New Horizons'' (2020)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: New Horizons}}\nA game in the series for [[Nintendo Switch]] was announced in a [[Nintendo Direct]] in September 2018 known as ''Animal Crossing: New Horizons''.{{efn|Known in Japan as {{nihongo|''Atsumare D\u014dbutsu no Mori''|\u3042\u3064\u307e\u308c \u3069\u3046\u3076\u3064\u306e\u68ee||lit. ''Gathering Animal Forest''}}}} Set on a deserted island, it was released on March 20, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Plante |first1=Chris |title=Animal Crossing: New Horizons looks magical, but is delayed to March 2020 |url=https://www.polygon.com/e3/2019/6/11/18661310/nintendo-direct-e3-2019-animal-crossing-new-horizons-trailer-release-date |website=Polygon |accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Spin-off games===\n\n====''Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer'' (2015)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer}}\n''[[Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer]]'' is a [[Social simulation game|community simulation]] video game for the [[Nintendo 3DS]] and the first spin-off of the ''Animal Crossing'' series. It was released in Japan on July 30, 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gematsu.com/2015/05/animal-crossing-happy-home-designer-japanese-release-date-set|title=Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer Japanese release date set|last=Romano|first=Sal|publisher=Gematsu|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> North America on September 25, 2015,<ref name=\"meta-hhd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/3ds/animal-crossing-happy-home-designer|title=Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer|publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> Europe on October 2, 2015,<ref name=\"nwd-hhd\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/news/40828/animal-crossing-happy-home-designer-bundles-announced-for-uk-and-australia |title=Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer Bundles Announced for UK and Australia |publisher=Nintendo World Report |last=Abou-Nasr |first=Adam |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> and Australia on October 3, 2015.<ref name=\"nwd-hhd\" /> The game revolves around designing houses for villagers based on their requests. By scanning [[Amiibo]] cards, players can unlock the ability to design special characters' houses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2015/06/animal_crossing_director_talks_more_about_happy_home_designer_and_amiibo|title=Animal Crossing Director Talks More About Happy Home Designer and amiibo|publisher=Nintendo Life|last=Vogel|first=Mitch|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> The game has a score of 66 out of 100 on [[Metacritic]], which signifies \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref name=\"meta-hhd\" />\n\n====''Animal Crossing: Amiibo Festival'' (2015)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: Amiibo Festival}}\n''[[Animal Crossing: Amiibo Festival]]'' is a [[Party video game|party]] video game for the [[Wii U]] released in November 2015 that heavily utilizes [[Amiibo]]. It was met with unfavorable reviews from critics.<ref name=\"meta-af\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/wii-u/animal-crossing-amiibo-festival/critic-reviews |title=Animal Crossing: amiibo Festival |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> It was developed by [[Nintendo Entertainment Planning & Development]] and [[NDcube]].\n\n====''Animal Crossing: Pocket Camp'' (2017)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: Pocket Camp}}\nIn April 2016, Nintendo announced that an ''Animal Crossing'' mobile game, later named as ''[[Animal Crossing: Pocket Camp]]'', would be released as a part of their [[Nintendo mobile games|mobile game lineup]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Seedhouse|first1=Alex|title=Next Nintendo Apps Will Use Fire Emblem & Animal Crossing Franchises|url=http://www.nintendo-insider.com/2016/04/next-nintendo-apps-will-use-fire-emblem-animal-crossing-franchises/|website=Nintendo Insider|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> The game was soft launched in Australia in October 2017, and released worldwide on November 21, 2017.\n\n===Apps===\n* ''[[Animal Crossing Plaza]]'', a [[Wii U system software#WaraWara Plaza|WaraWara Plaza]]-like app for [[Wii U]]. Limited time promotion for ''[[Animal Crossing: New Leaf]]''.\n* ''Animal Crossing Clock'', a Clock system app for [[Nintendo DSi]] and [[Nintendo 3DS]].\n* ''Animal Crossing Calculator'', a Calculator app for [[Nintendo DSi]] and [[Nintendo 3DS]].\n* ''Photos with Animal Crossing'', a Camera app for [[Nintendo 3DS]] allowing players to take photos with Animal Crossing characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nintendoeverything.com/photos-with-animal-crossing-nintendo-uk-summer-tour-2015-video/#disqus_thread|title=Photos with Animal Crossing - Nintendo UK Summer Tour 2015 video|work=Nintendo Everything|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception and legacy==\n{{Video game series reviews\n|updated = March 18, 2020\n|sales_title = Units sold<br />{{small|(in millions)}}\n\n|game1 = [[Animal Crossing (video game)|Animal Crossing]]\n|year1 = 2001\n|sales1 = 2.32<ref name=\"GC_NA_sales\"/><ref name=\"GC_JP_sales\"/>\n|mc1 = 87/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/gamecube/animal-crossing |title=''Animal Crossing'' (GCN) at Metacritic |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |publisher=Metacritic.com}}</ref>\n\n|game2 = [[Animal Crossing: Wild World]]\n|year2 = 2005\n|sales2 = 11.75<ref name=\"DS_sales\"/>\n|mc2 = 86/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/ds/animal-crossing-wild-world |title=Animal Crossing: Wild World |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n|game3 = [[Animal Crossing: City Folk]]\n|year3 = 2008\n|sales3 = 3.38<ref name=\"Wii_sales\"/>\n|mc3 = 73/100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/wii/animal-crossing-city-folk|title=''Animal Crossing: City Folk'' reviews|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n|game4 = [[Animal Crossing: New Leaf]]\n|year4 = 2012\n|sales4 = 12.21<ref name =\"3DS-top-sell\"/>\n|mc4 = 88/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/3ds/animal-crossing-new-leaf |title=Animal Crossing: New Leaf |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n|game5 = [[Animal Crossing: New Horizons]]\n|year5 = 2020\n|sales5 = 1.88\n|mc5 = 91/100<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/switch/animal-crossing-new-horizons|title=Animal Crossing: New Horizons |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe ''Animal Crossing'' games have garnered positive response.<ref name=\"IGN_GC_review\">{{cite web| title=Animal Crossing Review |last=Schneider |first=Peer |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/09/05/animal-crossing-review |date=September 5, 2002 |publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"IGN_DS_review\">{{cite web| title=Animal Crossing: Wild World Review |last=Harris |first=Craig |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2005/12/06/animal-crossing-wild-world |date=December 5, 2005 |publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"IGN_Wii_review\">{{cite web| title=Animal Crossing: City Folk Review |last=Harris |first=Craig |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/11/17/animal-crossing-city-folk-review |date=November 16, 2008 |publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> The first four main series games are among the [[List of best-selling video games|best-selling video games]] for their respective consoles. ''Animal Crossing'' has sold 2.32 million copies;<ref name=\"GC_NA_sales\">{{cite web|url=http://www.the-magicbox.com/Chart-USPlatinum.shtml|title=US Platinum Videogame Chart|publisher=The Magic Box|accessdate=February 13, 2017|date= December 27, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"GC_JP_sales\">{{cite web|url=http://www.japan-gamecharts.com/gc.php|title= Nintendo Gamecube Japanese Ranking|publisher= Japan Game Charts|date=May 6, 2007|accessdate=February 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070723025415/http://www.japan-gamecharts.com/gc.php|archive-date=July 23, 2007}}</ref> ''Wild World'' 11.75 million;<ref name=\"DS_sales\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/en/sales/software/ds.html|title=Financial  Results Briefing for Fiscal Year Ended March 2014|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|date=December 6, 2014| format=PDF|accessdate=February 13, 2017|pages=6}}</ref> ''City Folk'' 3.38 million;<ref name=\"Wii_sales\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2009/090508e.pdf#page=6|title=Financial Results Briefing for the Fiscal Year Ended March 2009: Supplementary Information|accessdate=February 13, 2017|date=May 8, 2009|work=Financial Results Briefing for the 69th Fiscal Term Ended March 2009|publisher=Nintendo|pages=6}}</ref> ''New Leaf'' 12.21 million,<ref name =\"3DS-top-sell\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/en/sales/software/3ds.html|title=IR Information : Sales Data - Top Selling Software Sales Units - Nintendo 3DS Software|website=Nintendo|accessdate=January 31, 2018}}</ref> and ''Happy Home Designer'' 3.04 million.<ref name=\"HHD sales\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2016/160427_4e.pdf |title=Supplementary Information about Earnings Release |date=April 27, 2016 |publisher=Nintendo |page=4 |format=PDF |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> ''Amiibo Festival'' was a critical and commercial failure; in Japan it has only sold 26,325 copies.<ref name=\"meta-af\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.4gamer.net/games/117/G011794/20151202067/ |title=\u300c\u30e2\u30f3\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30cf\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc\u30af\u30ed\u30b9\u300d\u72e9\u731f\u89e3\u7981\u3067\u521d\u9031\u8ca9\u58f2\u6570148\u4e07\u672c\u306e\u300c\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u30bd\u30d5\u30c8\u9031\u9593\u8ca9\u58f2\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0\uff0b\u300d |work=[[4Gamer.net]] |publisher=Aetas Inc. |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |language=Japanese}}</ref> In total, the ''Animal Crossing'' franchise has sold over 30 million units.\n\n===Female demographic===\nFormer president of [[Nintendo]], [[Satoru Iwata]] noted that 56% of people who pre-ordered ''[[Animal Crossing: New Leaf]]'' identify as female, with many of them purchasing a [[Nintendo 3DS]] specifically for the game. He found the game's success with adult women between the ages of 19 to 24 to be particularly noteworthy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.siliconera.com/2013/02/10/a-lot-of-women-bought-a-3ds-for-animal-crossing-new-leaf-in-japan/ |title=A Lot Of Women Bought A 3DS For Animal Crossing: New Leaf In Japan |website=Siliconera |date=February 10, 2013 |access-date=September 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.siliconera.com/2013/01/08/satoru-iwata-on-animal-crossing-sales-56-of-players-are-female/ |title=Satoru Iwata On Animal Crossing Sales, 56% Of Players Are Female |website=Siliconera |date=January 8, 2013 |access-date=September 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://mashable.com/2014/04/02/animal-crossing-gender-gaming/ |title=More Women Game Developers Means More Success, 'Animal Crossing' Director Says |website=Mashable |date=April 2, 2014 |access-date=September 17, 2018 |first=Chelsea |last=Stark}}</ref>\n\n==Other media==\n[[File:Villager (character).png|thumb|The male Villager, as depicted in ''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]'']]\nAn [[anime]] [[film adaptation]] of ''Wild World'', titled ''[[D\u014dbutsu no Mori (film)|D\u014dbutsu no Mori]]'', was released in Japan on December 16, 2006. The film was produced by [[OLM, Inc.]] and distributed by [[Toho]]. ''D\u014dbutsu no Mori'' earned [[Japanese yen|\u00a5]]1.8 billion (approximately $19.2 million) in the [[box office]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.rakuten.co.jp/movie/ranking/boxoffice/2007/ |title=2007\u5e74\u5ea6\u8208\u884c\u6210\u7e3e\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0 |language=Japanese |publisher=Rakuten |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121029165113/http://entertainment.rakuten.co.jp/movie/ranking/boxoffice/2007/ |archivedate=October 29, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the Wii game ''[[WarioWare: Smooth Moves]]'', released in Japan in 2006 and Europe, North America and Australia in 2007, there is a minigame that is modeled after Animal Crossing: Wild World, [[mariowiki:Animal Crossing: Wild World|under the same name]]. The player has to catch a fish using the same mechanics as the original game.\n\nThe 2008 Wii game ''[[Super Smash Bros. Brawl]]'' features elements from ''Wild World''. Most prominent is a stage based on the animal village, called \"Smashville\", which changes its scenery in accordance with the Wii system clock<ref name=\"smash_stage\">{{cite web| last= Sakurai |first= Masahiro |title= Smash Bros. DOJO!! Smashville |date=July 13, 2007 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/stages/stage06.html|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> and features a number of [[Video game music|songs]] remixed or extracted from the original game.<ref name=\"smash_music\">{{cite web| last= Sakurai |first= Masahiro |title= Smash Bros. DOJO!! Full Song List with Secret Songs |date=April 3, 2008 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/music/music24_list.html|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> Mr. Resetti and a pitfall seed, which appear in all ''Animal Crossing'' games, are available as an Assist Trophy and an item respectively.<ref name=\"smash_resetti\">{{cite web| last= Sakurai |first= Masahiro |title= Smash Bros. DOJO!! Mr. Resetti |date=September 26, 2007 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/items/assist/assist08.html|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"smash_pitfall\">{{cite web| last= Sakurai |first= Masahiro |title= Smash Bros. DOJO!! Pitfall |date=September 26, 2007 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/items/item06.html|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> ''Brawl'' also features 24 collectible trophies based on ''Animal Crossing'' characters and items.<ref name=\"smash_trophies\">{{cite web| last= Sakurai |first= Masahiro |title= Smash Bros. DOJO!! Trophy List |date=April 8, 2008 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/gamemode/various/various36_list.html|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''[[Wii Music]]'' features two playable songs from ''Animal Crossing''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.destructoid.com/here-s-the-rest-of-the-wii-music-tracklist-108429.phtml |title=Here's the rest of the Wii Music tracklist |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |last=North |first=Dale |date=October 20, 2008 |work=[[Destructoid]]}}</ref>\n\nThe minigame \"Animal Crossing: Sweet Day\" in ''[[Nintendo Land]]'' is based on the ''Animal Crossing'' game series. The objective of the game is for the Wii Remote players (1-4), to gather large amounts of candy scattered around the area and store them in their head without getting caught by the Gatekeepers, who are controlled using the two Wii U GamePad analog sticks.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnet.com/uk/products/nintendo-land-wii-u/review/2/ |title=Nintendo Land (Wii U) review |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |last=Petit |first=Carolyn |date=November 18, 2012 |work=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref>\n\nA playable character called \"Villager\" represents the ''Animal Crossing'' series as a fighter in ''[[Super Smash Bros. for Nintendo 3DS and Wii U]]'' and ''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]''. The character has both male and female forms, which are selected when choosing the character. His or her moves include the ability to catch other players in a net and firing Lloid the gyroid as a missile.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2468841,00.asp |title=How to Beast With Villager, Mega Man in Super Smash Bros. 3DS Demo |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |last=Torres |first=Timothy |date=September 13, 2014 |work=[[PC Magazine]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]}}</ref> Additionally, [[Isabelle (Animal Crossing)|Isabelle]] from ''New Leaf'' appears as an Assist Trophy,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wiiu-3ds/us/howto/entry6.html |title=Assist Trophies |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |work=[[Nintendo]]}}</ref> and later appeared as a standalone fighter in ''Ultimate''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/2018/09/13/super-smash-bros-ultimate-isabelle-animal-crossing/|title='Animal Crossing' Favorite Isabelle Joins 'Super Smash Bros. Ultimate' Roster|website=Comicbook.com}}</ref> Two new ''Animal Crossing'' stages appear in the games: \"Town & City\" from ''City Folk'' in the Wii U version, and \"Tortimer Island\" from ''New Leaf'' in the 3DS version.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wiiu-3ds/us/howto/entry4.html |title=Stages 1 |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |work=[[Nintendo]]}}</ref> \"Smashville\" from ''Brawl'' returns in the Wii U version.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/super-smash-bros-4-unlock-guide-characters-stages-how-wii-u-3ds-connect-10-million-us-sales-614833 |title=Super Smash Bros 4: Unlock Guide -- Characters and Stages; How Wii U and 3DS Connect; 10 Million US Sales |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |last=Bhat |first=Aditya |date=October 22, 2014 |work=[[International Business Times]] |publisher=[[IBT Media]]}}</ref>\n\nVillager and Isabelle are playable characters in ''[[Mario Kart 8]]'' via downloadable content, along with a racetrack based on ''Animal Crossing'' and a cup named after the series known as the \"Crossing Cup\".<ref name=\"Franchises coming to MK8\">{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/zelda-f-zero-coming-to-mario-kart-8-1627150730|title=Zelda, Animal Crossing Coming to Mario Kart 8 |publisher=Kotaku | first=Luke | last=Plunkett |date=August 26, 2014 |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> The two racers, along with the ''Animal Crossing'' track, were also included in the [[Nintendo Switch]] version of the game, ''[[Mario Kart 8 Deluxe]]'' along with a racing suit based on the series for the [[Mii]]. In June 2015, Isabelle and Mr. Resetti-themed cosmetics were added as costumes options for the player's \"Palico\" companion in ''[[Monster Hunter 4 Ultimate]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2015/06/monster_hunter_4_ultimate_june_dlc_brings_animal_crossing_devil_may_cry_and_awesome_designs|title=Monster Hunter 4 Ultimate June DLC Brings Animal Crossing, Devil May Cry and Awesome Designs|work=Nintendo Life|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Video games|Japan}}\n*[[List of Animal Crossing media|List of ''Animal Crossing'' media]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.animal-crossing.com/}}\n\n{{Animal Crossing series}}\n{{Nintendo franchises}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Animal Crossing| ]]\n[[Category:Life simulation games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo franchises]]\n[[Category:Social simulation video games]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises introduced in 2001]]\n[[Category:Video games adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Video game series developed by Nintendo}}\n{{about|the video game series|the first game in the series|Animal Crossing (video game)|other uses|}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game series\n| width = 400\n| title = Animal Crossing\n| image = Animal_Crossing_Logo.png\n| caption = ''Animal Crossing'' series logo\n| genre = [[Social simulation game|Social simulation]]\n| creator = [[Katsuya Eguchi]]\n| developer = {{Unbulleted list|[[Nintendo EAD]]|[[Nintendo Entertainment Planning & Development|Nintendo EPD]]|[[NDcube]]}}\n| publisher = [[Nintendo]]\n| platforms = {{Hlist|[[Nintendo 64]]|[[iQue Player]]|[[GameCube]]|[[Wii]]|[[Wii U]]|[[Nintendo DS]]|[[Nintendo 3DS]]|[[iOS]]|[[Android (operating system)|Android]]|[[Nintendo Switch]]}}\n| first release version = ''[[Animal Crossing (video game)|Animal Crossing]]''\n| first release date = April 14, 2001\n| latest release version = ''[[Animal Crossing: New Horizons]]''\n| latest release date = March 20, 2020\n| spinoffs = {{Unbulleted list|''[[Happy Home Designer]]''|''[[Amiibo Festival]]''|''[[Pocket Camp]]''}}\n}}\n\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Animal Crossing'''''|\u3069\u3046\u3076\u3064\u306e\u68ee|D\u014dbutsu no Mori|''Animal Forest''|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a [[social simulation game|social simulation]] [[video game]] series developed and published by [[Nintendo]] and created by [[Katsuya Eguchi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.droidgamers.com/index.php/apps/7395-while-animal-crossing-may-never-see-a-mobile-game-there-could-be-companion-apps-on-the-way|title=While Animal Crossing may never see a mobile game, there could be companion apps on the way|author=Andrew H|website=droidgamers.com|date=March 27, 2014|accessdate=February 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304072130/http://www.droidgamers.com/index.php/apps/7395-while-animal-crossing-may-never-see-a-mobile-game-there-could-be-companion-apps-on-the-way|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/no-retro-games-in-future-animal-crossings-with-one-poss-512085493|title=No Retro Games in Future Animal Crossings\u2014With One Possible Exception|author=Stephen Totilo|website=kotaku.com|date=June 8, 2013|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/e3-08-nintendo-press-conference/|title=E3 08: Nintendo Press Conference|author=Brett Elston|website=gamesradar.com|date=July 15, 2008|accessdate=February 24, 2016}}</ref> In ''Animal Crossing'', the [[player character]] is a human who lives in a village inhabited by various [[Anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]] animals, carrying out various activities such as fishing, bug catching, and fossil hunting. The series is notable for its [[Nonlinear gameplay|open-ended]] gameplay and extensive use of the [[video game console]]'s internal clock and calendar to simulate [[Real time (media)|real passage of time]].\n\nSince its [[Animal Crossing (video game)|initial release]] in 2001, five ''Animal Crossing'' games have been released worldwide, one each for the [[Nintendo 64]]/[[iQue Player]] (enhanced and reissued for the [[GameCube]]), [[Nintendo DS]], [[Wii]], [[Nintendo 3DS]] and [[Nintendo Switch]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techradar.com/news/animal-crossing-on-nintendo-switch|title=Animal Crossing on Nintendo Switch: release date, news and features|last=Hood|first=Vic|last2=Gaming|first2=Nick Pino 2019-06-18T17:06:19Z|website=TechRadar|language=en|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref> The series has been both critically and commercially successful and has sold over 30 million units worldwide. Three spin-off games have also been released: ''[[Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer]]'' for [[Nintendo 3DS]], ''[[Animal Crossing: Amiibo Festival]]'' for [[Wii U]], and ''[[Animal Crossing: Pocket Camp]]'' for mobile devices.\n\n== Common elements ==\n\n=== Characters ===\nWhile the series features various villagers for each title, certain prominent characters return in each series installment. [[Tom Nook]] is a [[Japanese raccoon dog|tanuki]] character who functions as both a shop owner and real estate broker, giving the player a loan for their house and allowing them to pay it back with no interest. He is one of the only residents of the town to follow a [[Capitalism|capitalist]] ethos. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/tom-nook-needs-to-get-with-the-times-1829149177|title=Tom Nook Needs To Get With The Times|last=Jackson|first=Gita|website=Kotaku|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> [[Mr. Resetti]] is a mole character who appears from underground whenever players shut off the game without saving, berating them for circumventing one of the game's systems. Due to a new [[autosave]] function, he was \"laid off\" from his job in ''Animal Crossing: New Horizons'', although he has gotten a new job as the Rescue Service operator. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2019/06/17/animal-crossing-new-horizons-autosave-resettis-job/|title=Animal Crossing New Horizons has autosave, so Resetti's out of a job|date=2019-06-17|website=VG247|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref>\n\n[[K.K. Slider]] is a canine traveling musician based on series composer [[Kazumi Totaka]], and plays on certain nights in the town's club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2013/05/profile_kazumi_totaka_the_man_behind_animal_crossings_kk_slider|title=Profile: Kazumi Totaka - The Man Behind Animal Crossing's K.K. Slider|last=Life|first=Nintendo|date=2013-05-08|website=Nintendo Life|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> Afterwards, he gifts the player a free copy of the song played, saying that his music \"wants to be free\". This was seen by some fans as tacit support for [[music piracy]], although Nintendo denied that it was intended as [[social commentary]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/19/technology/social-commentary-or-just-a-dogs-opinion.html|title=Social Commentary, or Just a Dog's Opinion?|last=Jr|first=Tom Zeller|date=2005-12-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-08-18|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===Gameplay===\nIn the ''Animal Crossing'' games, the player assumes the role of a human child, aged between 9-13, who moves into a rural village populated with anthropomorphic animals and lives there indefinitely. Gameplay is [[Nonlinear gameplay|open-ended]]: players have no defined objectives, but are instead encouraged to spend their time in the village performing any number of activities, which include collecting items, planting plants or other items, and socializing with the village's residents. ''Animal Crossing'' games are played in [[Real time (media)|real time]], utilizing the [[video game console]]'s internal clock and calendar. Thus, passage of time in the game world reflects that in reality, as well as the current season and time of day. Some in-game events, such as holidays or the growth of a tree, occur at certain times or require some duration of time to have passed.<ref name=\"IGN_GC_preview\"/>\n\nOne notable feature of the ''Animal Crossing'' series is the high level of customization available, some of which affects the outcome of the game.<ref name=\"IGN_GC_review\" /> The [[player character]] is both named and gendered by the real life player at the start of the game, and their appearance can be modified by buying or designing custom clothes and accessories or changing the hairstyle (introduced in ''[[Animal Crossing: Wild World|Wild World]]''). The player's house can also be furnished, decorated, and later expanded: the player can purchase and collect furniture and place it anywhere in the house, as well as change both the wallpaper and floor designs. While its terrain, building locations, and initial residents are randomly generated when the game is first begun (except in ''Animal Crossing: New Leaf'', in which the player decides between four given towns, and ''Animal Crossing: New Horizons'', in which the player similarly decides between four given islands), the village's name and anthem, as well as some of the residents' catchphrases, are also determined by the player.<ref name=\"IGN_GC_review\"/>\n\nCollecting items is a major facet of ''Animal Crossing'': the player can explore the village and gather objects, including fruit from trees, seashells, and discarded items. Nearly all objects can be sold for Bells, the in-game currency. Players collect objects to obtain more Bells, which can then be used to buy furniture and clothing, purchase home expansions, invest in stocks, and play games. A number of specialized tools are available for other activities such as fishing and insect collecting. Special items, such as fossils and paintings, may be donated to the village museum. The player can choose to socialize with the other animal residents by engaging in conversation, sending and receiving letters, bartering, or playing hide-and-seek. Residents may move in or out of the village depending on the player's actions.\n\nAll installments of ''Animal Crossing'' allow some form of communication between players, both offline and [[Online game|online]]. A single village can house up to four human players, though only one can be exploring the village at any given time.<ref name=\"IGN_GC_preview\">{{cite web| title=Animal Crossing Preview |last=Schneider |first=Peer |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/05/30/animal-crossing |date=May 30, 2002 |publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> The players can interact via written messages through the village post office or bulletin board. The [[GameCube]] iteration allowed players to travel to other villages by trading [[Nintendo GameCube#Memory and storage|memory cards]] written with the game data,<ref name=\"IGN_GC_review\"/> but all subsequent installments allow players to travel and interact online via [[Nintendo Wi-Fi Connection]], although ''[[Animal Crossing: City Folk|City Folk]]'' also allows the DS Suitcase to travel to others' towns.<ref name=\"IGN_DS_review\"/><ref name=\"IGN_Wii_review\"/>\n\n==Games==\n\n{{Timeline of release years\n| summary = Timeline of releases in the ''Animal Crossing'' series, from 2001 to present.\n| range1       = 2001 \u2013\n| range1_color = #ffc836 #e5d2ac <!-- Based on series logo -->\n| 2001 = ''[[Animal Crossing (video game)|Animal Crossing]]''\n| 2005 = ''[[Animal Crossing: Wild World|Wild World]]''\n| 2008 = ''[[Animal Crossing: City Folk|City Folk]]''\n| 2012 = ''[[Animal Crossing: New Leaf|New Leaf]]''\n| 2015a = ''[[Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer|Happy Home Designer]]''\n| 2015b = ''[[Animal Crossing: Amiibo Festival|Amiibo Festival]]''\n| 2016 = ''[[Animal Crossing: New Leaf|New Leaf \u2013 Welcome Amiibo]]''\n| 2017 = ''[[Animal Crossing: Pocket Camp|Pocket Camp]]''\n| 2020 = ''[[Animal Crossing: New Horizons|New Horizons]]''\n}}\n\n===Main series===\n\n====''Animal Crossing'' (2001)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing (video game)}}\n''Animal Crossing''{{efn|Known in Japan as {{nihongo|''D\u014dbutsu no Mori''|\u3069\u3046\u3076\u3064\u306e\u68ee||lit. ''Animal Forest''}}}} originally released in Japan for the [[Nintendo 64]] in 2001. It was enhanced and released on the [[GameCube]] the same year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/11/13/the-evolution-of-animal-crossing-2?page=2 |title=The Evolution of Animal Crossing (page 2) |last=Harris |first=Craig |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> This version was localized and released in North America on September 16, 2002, Australia on October 17, 2003, and Europe on September 24, 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/games/action-replay-ultimate-codes-animal-crossing/gcn-16562 |title=Animal Crossing Review |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> An extended version titled \"D\u014dbutsu no Mori e+\" was released on June 27, 2003 in Japan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/games/doubutsu-no-mori/gcn-552545 |title=Doubutsu no Mori e+ |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> The Nintendo 64 version of the game was released in China in 2006 for [[iQue Player]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ique.com/games/21041.htm |title=Animal Forest |publisher=iQue Ltd. |language=Chinese |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====''Animal Crossing: Wild World'' (2005)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: Wild World}}\n''Animal Crossing: Wild World''{{efn|Known in Japan as {{nihongo|''Oideyo D\u014dbutsu no Mori''|\u304a\u3044\u3067\u3088 \u3069\u3046\u3076\u3064\u306e\u68ee||lit. ''Come to Animal Forest''}}}} was released for the [[Nintendo DS]] in Japan on November 23, 2005, North America on December 5, 2005, Australia on December 8, 2005, and Europe on March 31, 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/games/animal-crossing-wild-world/nds-682878 |title=Animal Crossing: Wild World Review |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> It was the first game in the series to use [[Nintendo Wi-Fi Connection]]. The game was later re-released on the [[Wii U]] [[Virtual Console]] on October 13, 2016, although its Wi-Fi multiplayer feature is unavailable due to the [[Nintendo Wi-Fi Connection#Closing|discontinuation]] of Nintendo Wi-Fi Connection.\n\n====''Animal Crossing: City Folk'' (2008)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: City Folk}}\n''Animal Crossing: City Folk'',{{efn|Known in Japan as {{nihongo|''Machi e Ik\u014d yo D\u014dbutsu no Mori''|\u8857\u3078\u884c\u3053\u3046\u3088 \u3069\u3046\u3076\u3064\u306e\u68ee||lit. ''Let's Go to the City: Animal Forest''}}}} known as ''Animal Crossing: Let's Go to the City'' in Europe and Australia, was released for the [[Wii]] in North America on November 16, 2008, Japan on November 20, 2008, Australia on December 4, 2008, and Europe on December 5, 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/games/animal-crossing-city-folk/wii-748892 |title=Animal Crossing: City Folk Review |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> It was later released in South Korea in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendo.co.kr/Wii/software/animal_crossing/main.php |title=\ud0c0\uc6b4\uc73c\ub85c \ub180\ub7ec\uac00\uc694 \ub3d9\ubb3c\uc758 \uc232 |publisher=Nintendo |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |language=Korean}}</ref> It was the first Wii game to utilize the [[Wii Speak]], an accessory that allows players to talk to each other during online play.\n\n====''Animal Crossing: New Leaf'' (2012)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: New Leaf}}\n''Animal Crossing: New Leaf''{{efn|Known in Japan as {{nihongo|''Tobidase D\u014dbutsu no Mori''|\u3068\u3073\u3060\u305b \u3069\u3046\u3076\u3064\u306e\u68ee||lit. ''Jump Out Animal Forest''}}}} was announced at [[E3 2010]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/06/15/e3-2010-animal-crossing-3ds-announced|title=E3 2010: Animal Crossing 3DS Announced|publisher=IGN|last=Thomas|first=Lucas M.|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> It was released for the [[Nintendo 3DS]] in Japan on November 8, 2012, North America on June 9, 2013, Europe on June 14, 2013, and Australia on June 15, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/games/animal-crossing-3ds/3ds-77803 |title=Animal Crossing: New Leaf |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> For the first time in the series, players are appointed to the role of Mayor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/10/25/animal-crossing-3ds-has-a-new-name|title=Animal Crossing 3DS Has a New Name|last=Drake|first=Audrey|publisher=IGN|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\nIn November 2016, a new update was released along with \"Welcome Amiibo\" in North America and Europe, adding several new locations, items and activities.<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome Amiibo|url=http://www.mojenintendo.cz/animal-crossing-new-leaf-welcome-amiibocard/|website=mojenintendo.cz|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====''Animal Crossing: New Horizons'' (2020)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: New Horizons}}\nA game in the series for [[Nintendo Switch]] was announced in a [[Nintendo Direct]] in September 2018 known as ''Animal Crossing: New Horizons''.{{efn|Known in Japan as {{nihongo|''Atsumare D\u014dbutsu no Mori''|\u3042\u3064\u307e\u308c \u3069\u3046\u3076\u3064\u306e\u68ee||lit. ''Gathering Animal Forest''}}}} Set on a deserted island, it was released on March 20, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Plante |first1=Chris |title=Animal Crossing: New Horizons looks magical, but is delayed to March 2020 |url=https://www.polygon.com/e3/2019/6/11/18661310/nintendo-direct-e3-2019-animal-crossing-new-horizons-trailer-release-date |website=Polygon |accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Spin-off games===\n\n====''Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer'' (2015)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer}}\n''[[Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer]]'' is a [[Social simulation game|community simulation]] video game for the [[Nintendo 3DS]] and the first spin-off of the ''Animal Crossing'' series. It was released in Japan on July 30, 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gematsu.com/2015/05/animal-crossing-happy-home-designer-japanese-release-date-set|title=Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer Japanese release date set|last=Romano|first=Sal|publisher=Gematsu|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> North America on September 25, 2015,<ref name=\"meta-hhd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/3ds/animal-crossing-happy-home-designer|title=Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer|publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> Europe on October 2, 2015,<ref name=\"nwd-hhd\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/news/40828/animal-crossing-happy-home-designer-bundles-announced-for-uk-and-australia |title=Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer Bundles Announced for UK and Australia |publisher=Nintendo World Report |last=Abou-Nasr |first=Adam |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> and Australia on October 3, 2015.<ref name=\"nwd-hhd\" /> The game revolves around designing houses for villagers based on their requests. By scanning [[Amiibo]] cards, players can unlock the ability to design special characters' houses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2015/06/animal_crossing_director_talks_more_about_happy_home_designer_and_amiibo|title=Animal Crossing Director Talks More About Happy Home Designer and amiibo|publisher=Nintendo Life|last=Vogel|first=Mitch|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> The game has a score of 66 out of 100 on [[Metacritic]], which signifies \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref name=\"meta-hhd\" />\n\n====''Animal Crossing: Amiibo Festival'' (2015)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: Amiibo Festival}}\n''[[Animal Crossing: Amiibo Festival]]'' is a [[Party video game|party]] video game for the [[Wii U]] released in November 2015 that heavily utilizes [[Amiibo]]. It was met with unfavorable reviews from critics.<ref name=\"meta-af\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/wii-u/animal-crossing-amiibo-festival/critic-reviews |title=Animal Crossing: amiibo Festival |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> It was developed by [[Nintendo Entertainment Planning & Development]] and [[NDcube]].\n\n====''Animal Crossing: Pocket Camp'' (2017)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: Pocket Camp}}\nIn April 2016, Nintendo announced that an ''Animal Crossing'' mobile game, later named as ''[[Animal Crossing: Pocket Camp]]'', would be released as a part of their [[Nintendo mobile games|mobile game lineup]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Seedhouse|first1=Alex|title=Next Nintendo Apps Will Use Fire Emblem & Animal Crossing Franchises|url=http://www.nintendo-insider.com/2016/04/next-nintendo-apps-will-use-fire-emblem-animal-crossing-franchises/|website=Nintendo Insider|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> The game was soft launched in Australia in October 2017, and released worldwide on November 21, 2017.\n\n===Apps===\n* ''[[Animal Crossing Plaza]]'', a [[Wii U system software#WaraWara Plaza|WaraWara Plaza]]-like app for [[Wii U]]. Limited time promotion for ''[[Animal Crossing: New Leaf]]''.\n* ''Animal Crossing Clock'', a Clock system app for [[Nintendo DSi]] and [[Nintendo 3DS]].\n* ''Animal Crossing Calculator'', a Calculator app for [[Nintendo DSi]] and [[Nintendo 3DS]].\n* ''Photos with Animal Crossing'', a Camera app for [[Nintendo 3DS]] allowing players to take photos with Animal Crossing characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nintendoeverything.com/photos-with-animal-crossing-nintendo-uk-summer-tour-2015-video/#disqus_thread|title=Photos with Animal Crossing - Nintendo UK Summer Tour 2015 video|work=Nintendo Everything|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception and legacy==\n{{Video game series reviews\n|updated = March 18, 2020\n|sales_title = Units sold<br />{{small|(in millions)}}\n\n|game1 = [[Animal Crossing (video game)|Animal Crossing]]\n|year1 = 2001\n|sales1 = 2.32<ref name=\"GC_NA_sales\"/><ref name=\"GC_JP_sales\"/>\n|mc1 = 87/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/gamecube/animal-crossing |title=''Animal Crossing'' (GCN) at Metacritic |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |publisher=Metacritic.com}}</ref>\n\n|game2 = [[Animal Crossing: Wild World]]\n|year2 = 2005\n|sales2 = 11.75<ref name=\"DS_sales\"/>\n|mc2 = 86/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/ds/animal-crossing-wild-world |title=Animal Crossing: Wild World |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n|game3 = [[Animal Crossing: City Folk]]\n|year3 = 2008\n|sales3 = 3.38<ref name=\"Wii_sales\"/>\n|mc3 = 73/100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/wii/animal-crossing-city-folk|title=''Animal Crossing: City Folk'' reviews|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n|game4 = [[Animal Crossing: New Leaf]]\n|year4 = 2012\n|sales4 = 12.21<ref name =\"3DS-top-sell\"/>\n|mc4 = 88/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/3ds/animal-crossing-new-leaf |title=Animal Crossing: New Leaf |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n|game5 = [[Animal Crossing: New Horizons]]\n|year5 = 2020\n|sales5 = 1.88\n|mc5 = 91/100<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/switch/animal-crossing-new-horizons|title=Animal Crossing: New Horizons |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe ''Animal Crossing'' games have garnered positive response.<ref name=\"IGN_GC_review\">{{cite web| title=Animal Crossing Review |last=Schneider |first=Peer |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/09/05/animal-crossing-review |date=September 5, 2002 |publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"IGN_DS_review\">{{cite web| title=Animal Crossing: Wild World Review |last=Harris |first=Craig |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2005/12/06/animal-crossing-wild-world |date=December 5, 2005 |publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"IGN_Wii_review\">{{cite web| title=Animal Crossing: City Folk Review |last=Harris |first=Craig |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/11/17/animal-crossing-city-folk-review |date=November 16, 2008 |publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> The first four main series games are among the [[List of best-selling video games|best-selling video games]] for their respective consoles. ''Animal Crossing'' has sold 2.32 million copies;<ref name=\"GC_NA_sales\">{{cite web|url=http://www.the-magicbox.com/Chart-USPlatinum.shtml|title=US Platinum Videogame Chart|publisher=The Magic Box|accessdate=February 13, 2017|date= December 27, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"GC_JP_sales\">{{cite web|url=http://www.japan-gamecharts.com/gc.php|title= Nintendo Gamecube Japanese Ranking|publisher= Japan Game Charts|date=May 6, 2007|accessdate=February 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070723025415/http://www.japan-gamecharts.com/gc.php|archive-date=July 23, 2007}}</ref> ''Wild World'' 11.75 million;<ref name=\"DS_sales\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/en/sales/software/ds.html|title=Financial  Results Briefing for Fiscal Year Ended March 2014|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|date=December 6, 2014| format=PDF|accessdate=February 13, 2017|pages=6}}</ref> ''City Folk'' 3.38 million;<ref name=\"Wii_sales\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2009/090508e.pdf#page=6|title=Financial Results Briefing for the Fiscal Year Ended March 2009: Supplementary Information|accessdate=February 13, 2017|date=May 8, 2009|work=Financial Results Briefing for the 69th Fiscal Term Ended March 2009|publisher=Nintendo|pages=6}}</ref> ''New Leaf'' 12.21 million,<ref name =\"3DS-top-sell\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/en/sales/software/3ds.html|title=IR Information : Sales Data - Top Selling Software Sales Units - Nintendo 3DS Software|website=Nintendo|accessdate=January 31, 2018}}</ref> and ''Happy Home Designer'' 3.04 million.<ref name=\"HHD sales\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2016/160427_4e.pdf |title=Supplementary Information about Earnings Release |date=April 27, 2016 |publisher=Nintendo |page=4 |format=PDF |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> ''Amiibo Festival'' was a critical and commercial failure; in Japan it has only sold 26,325 copies.<ref name=\"meta-af\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.4gamer.net/games/117/G011794/20151202067/ |title=\u300c\u30e2\u30f3\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30cf\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc\u30af\u30ed\u30b9\u300d\u72e9\u731f\u89e3\u7981\u3067\u521d\u9031\u8ca9\u58f2\u6570148\u4e07\u672c\u306e\u300c\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u30bd\u30d5\u30c8\u9031\u9593\u8ca9\u58f2\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0\uff0b\u300d |work=[[4Gamer.net]] |publisher=Aetas Inc. |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |language=Japanese}}</ref> In total, the ''Animal Crossing'' franchise has sold over 30 million units.\n\n===Female demographic===\nFormer president of [[Nintendo]], [[Satoru Iwata]] noted that 56% of people who pre-ordered ''[[Animal Crossing: New Leaf]]'' identify as female, with many of them purchasing a [[Nintendo 3DS]] specifically for the game. He found the game's success with adult women between the ages of 19 to 24 to be particularly noteworthy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.siliconera.com/2013/02/10/a-lot-of-women-bought-a-3ds-for-animal-crossing-new-leaf-in-japan/ |title=A Lot Of Women Bought A 3DS For Animal Crossing: New Leaf In Japan |website=Siliconera |date=February 10, 2013 |access-date=September 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.siliconera.com/2013/01/08/satoru-iwata-on-animal-crossing-sales-56-of-players-are-female/ |title=Satoru Iwata On Animal Crossing Sales, 56% Of Players Are Female |website=Siliconera |date=January 8, 2013 |access-date=September 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://mashable.com/2014/04/02/animal-crossing-gender-gaming/ |title=More Women Game Developers Means More Success, 'Animal Crossing' Director Says |website=Mashable |date=April 2, 2014 |access-date=September 17, 2018 |first=Chelsea |last=Stark}}</ref>\n\n==Other media==\n[[File:Villager (character).png|thumb|The male Villager, as depicted in ''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]'']]\nAn [[anime]] [[film adaptation]] of ''Wild World'', titled ''[[D\u014dbutsu no Mori (film)|D\u014dbutsu no Mori]]'', was released in Japan on December 16, 2006. The film was produced by [[OLM, Inc.]] and distributed by [[Toho]]. ''D\u014dbutsu no Mori'' earned [[Japanese yen|\u00a5]]1.8 billion (approximately $19.2 million) in the [[box office]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.rakuten.co.jp/movie/ranking/boxoffice/2007/ |title=2007\u5e74\u5ea6\u8208\u884c\u6210\u7e3e\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0 |language=Japanese |publisher=Rakuten |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121029165113/http://entertainment.rakuten.co.jp/movie/ranking/boxoffice/2007/ |archivedate=October 29, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the Wii game ''[[WarioWare: Smooth Moves]]'', released in Japan in 2006 and Europe, North America and Australia in 2007, there is a minigame that is modeled after Animal Crossing: Wild World, [[mariowiki:Animal Crossing: Wild World|under the same name]]. The player has to catch a fish using the same mechanics as the original game.\n\nThe 2008 Wii game ''[[Super Smash Bros. Brawl]]'' features elements from ''Wild World''. Most prominent is a stage based on the animal village, called \"Smashville\", which changes its scenery in accordance with the Wii system clock<ref name=\"smash_stage\">{{cite web| last= Sakurai |first= Masahiro |title= Smash Bros. DOJO!! Smashville |date=July 13, 2007 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/stages/stage06.html|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> and features a number of [[Video game music|songs]] remixed or extracted from the original game.<ref name=\"smash_music\">{{cite web| last= Sakurai |first= Masahiro |title= Smash Bros. DOJO!! Full Song List with Secret Songs |date=April 3, 2008 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/music/music24_list.html|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> Mr. Resetti and a pitfall seed, which appear in all ''Animal Crossing'' games, are available as an Assist Trophy and an item respectively.<ref name=\"smash_resetti\">{{cite web| last= Sakurai |first= Masahiro |title= Smash Bros. DOJO!! Mr. Resetti |date=September 26, 2007 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/items/assist/assist08.html|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"smash_pitfall\">{{cite web| last= Sakurai |first= Masahiro |title= Smash Bros. DOJO!! Pitfall |date=September 26, 2007 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/items/item06.html|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> ''Brawl'' also features 24 collectible trophies based on ''Animal Crossing'' characters and items.<ref name=\"smash_trophies\">{{cite web| last= Sakurai |first= Masahiro |title= Smash Bros. DOJO!! Trophy List |date=April 8, 2008 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/gamemode/various/various36_list.html|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''[[Wii Music]]'' features two playable songs from ''Animal Crossing''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.destructoid.com/here-s-the-rest-of-the-wii-music-tracklist-108429.phtml |title=Here's the rest of the Wii Music tracklist |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |last=North |first=Dale |date=October 20, 2008 |work=[[Destructoid]]}}</ref>\n\nThe minigame \"Animal Crossing: Sweet Day\" in ''[[Nintendo Land]]'' is based on the ''Animal Crossing'' game series. The objective of the game is for the Wii Remote players (1-4), to gather large amounts of candy scattered around the area and store them in their head without getting caught by the Gatekeepers, who are controlled using the two Wii U GamePad analog sticks.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnet.com/uk/products/nintendo-land-wii-u/review/2/ |title=Nintendo Land (Wii U) review |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |last=Petit |first=Carolyn |date=November 18, 2012 |work=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref>\n\nA playable character called \"Villager\" represents the ''Animal Crossing'' series as a fighter in ''[[Super Smash Bros. for Nintendo 3DS and Wii U]]'' and ''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]''. The character has both male and female forms, which are selected when choosing the character. His or her moves include the ability to catch other players in a net and firing Lloid the gyroid as a missile.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2468841,00.asp |title=How to Beast With Villager, Mega Man in Super Smash Bros. 3DS Demo |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |last=Torres |first=Timothy |date=September 13, 2014 |work=[[PC Magazine]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]}}</ref> Additionally, [[Isabelle (Animal Crossing)|Isabelle]] from ''New Leaf'' appears as an Assist Trophy,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wiiu-3ds/us/howto/entry6.html |title=Assist Trophies |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |work=[[Nintendo]]}}</ref> and later appeared as a standalone fighter in ''Ultimate''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/2018/09/13/super-smash-bros-ultimate-isabelle-animal-crossing/|title='Animal Crossing' Favorite Isabelle Joins 'Super Smash Bros. Ultimate' Roster|website=Comicbook.com}}</ref> Two new ''Animal Crossing'' stages appear in the games: \"Town & City\" from ''City Folk'' in the Wii U version, and \"Tortimer Island\" from ''New Leaf'' in the 3DS version.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wiiu-3ds/us/howto/entry4.html |title=Stages 1 |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |work=[[Nintendo]]}}</ref> \"Smashville\" from ''Brawl'' returns in the Wii U version.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/super-smash-bros-4-unlock-guide-characters-stages-how-wii-u-3ds-connect-10-million-us-sales-614833 |title=Super Smash Bros 4: Unlock Guide -- Characters and Stages; How Wii U and 3DS Connect; 10 Million US Sales |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |last=Bhat |first=Aditya |date=October 22, 2014 |work=[[International Business Times]] |publisher=[[IBT Media]]}}</ref>\n\nVillager and Isabelle are playable characters in ''[[Mario Kart 8]]'' via downloadable content, along with a racetrack based on ''Animal Crossing'' and a cup named after the series known as the \"Crossing Cup\".<ref name=\"Franchises coming to MK8\">{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/zelda-f-zero-coming-to-mario-kart-8-1627150730|title=Zelda, Animal Crossing Coming to Mario Kart 8 |publisher=Kotaku | first=Luke | last=Plunkett |date=August 26, 2014 |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> The two racers, along with the ''Animal Crossing'' track, were also included in the [[Nintendo Switch]] version of the game, ''[[Mario Kart 8 Deluxe]]'' along with a racing suit based on the series for the [[Mii]]. In June 2015, Isabelle and Mr. Resetti-themed cosmetics were added as costumes options for the player's \"Palico\" companion in ''[[Monster Hunter 4 Ultimate]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2015/06/monster_hunter_4_ultimate_june_dlc_brings_animal_crossing_devil_may_cry_and_awesome_designs|title=Monster Hunter 4 Ultimate June DLC Brings Animal Crossing, Devil May Cry and Awesome Designs|work=Nintendo Life|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Video games|Japan}}\n*[[List of Animal Crossing media|List of ''Animal Crossing'' media]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.animal-crossing.com/}}\n\n{{Animal Crossing series}}\n{{Nintendo franchises}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Animal Crossing| ]]\n[[Category:Life simulation games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo franchises]]\n[[Category:Social simulation video games]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises introduced in 2001]]\n[[Category:Video games adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n", "name_user": "47.16.175.232", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Animal_Crossing"}
{"title_page": "Godzilla vs. Kong", "text_new": "{{About|the upcoming 2020 film ware two kings meet and fight each other with some humans beside them.\n{{short description|2020 film directed by Adam Wingard}}\n{{Use American English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Godzilla vs. Kong\n| image          = File:Godzilla vs. Kong - licensing promotional poster.jpg\n| caption        = Two kings fighting\n\n\n| director       = [[Adam Wingard]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Mary Parent]]\n* Alex Garcia\n* Eric McLeod\n* Brian Rogers\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Terry Rossio]] <!-- DO NOT ADD MICHAEL DOUGHERTY AND ZACH SHIELDS! Their contributions were only minor, not enough to merit them screenwriting credit. As of this moment, Warner Bros has named Rossio as the sole screenwriter. DO NOT ADD any additional writing credits until the WGA reveals the final writing credit list. -->\n}}\n| story          =\n| based on       = {{based on|[[Godzilla]]|[[Toho]]}}<br>{{based on|[[King Kong]]|[[Edgar Wallace]] and [[Merian C. Cooper]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Alexander Skarsg\u00e5rd]]\n* [[Millie Bobby Brown]]\n* [[Rebecca Hall]]\n* [[Brian Tyree Henry]]\n* [[Shun Oguri]]\n* [[Eiza Gonz\u00e1lez]]\n* [[Jessica Henwick]]\n* [[Julian Dennison]]\n* [[Kyle Chandler]]\n* [[Zhang Ziyi]]\n* [[Demi\u00e1n Bichir]]\n}}\n| music          = \n| cinematography = [[Ben Seresin]]\n| editing        = Josh Schaeffer\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Legendary Entertainment|Legendary Pictures]]\n}}\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Warner Bros. Pictures]] (Worldwide)\n* Toho (Japan)\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2020|11|20|United States}}\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| gross          =\n}}\n\n'''''Godzilla vs. Kong''''' is an upcoming American [[monster film]] directed by [[Adam Wingard]]. A sequel to ''[[Godzilla: King of the Monsters (2019 film)|Godzilla: King of the Monsters]]'' (2019) and ''[[Kong: Skull Island]]'' (2017), it is the fourth film in [[Legendary Entertainment|Legendary]]'s [[MonsterVerse]]. The film is also the 36th film in the [[Godzilla (franchise)|''Godzilla'' franchise]], the 12th film in the [[King Kong (franchise)|''King Kong'' franchise]], and the fourth ''Godzilla'' film to be completely produced by a Hollywood studio.{{efn|The American releases of ''[[Godzilla (1954 film)|Godzilla]]'' (''[[Godzilla, King of the Monsters!]]''), ''[[King Kong vs. Godzilla#English version|King Kong vs. Godzilla]]'', and ''[[The Return of Godzilla]]'' (''[[Godzilla 1985]]'') featured additional footage with American actors filmed by small Hollywood production companies that merged the American footage with the original Japanese footage in order to appeal to American audiences.{{sfn|Kalat|2010|p=25}} ''[[Invasion of Astro-Monster]]'' was the first ''Godzilla'' film to be co-produced between a Japanese studio (Toho) and an American studio ([[UPA (animation studio)|UPA]]). The first ''Godzilla'' film to be completely produced by a Hollywood studio was ''[[Godzilla (1998 film)|Godzilla]]'' (1998).}} The film stars [[Alexander Skarsg\u00e5rd]], [[Millie Bobby Brown]], [[Rebecca Hall]], [[Brian Tyree Henry]], [[Shun Oguri]], [[Eiza Gonz\u00e1lez]], [[Jessica Henwick]], [[Julian Dennison]], [[Kyle Chandler]], [[Zhang Ziyi]], and [[Demi\u00e1n Bichir]].\n\nThe project was announced in October 2015 when Legendary announced plans for a shared cinematic universe between [[Godzilla]] and [[King Kong]]. The film's writers room was assembled in March 2017, and Wingard was announced as the director in May 2017. [[Principal photography]] began in November 2018 in [[Hawaii]], [[Australia]], and [[Hong Kong]] and [[Wrap (filmmaking)|wrapped]] in April 2019. ''Godzilla vs. Kong'' is scheduled to be released on November 20, 2020, in 2D, [[3D film|3D]], and [[IMAX]].\n\n==Premise==\n{{quote|In a time when monsters walk the Earth, humanity's fight for its future sets Godzilla and Kong on a collision course that will see the two most powerful forces of nature on the planet collide in a spectacular battle for the ages. As Monarch embarks on a perilous mission into uncharted terrain and unearths clues to the Titans' origins, a human conspiracy threatens to wipe the creatures, both good and bad, from the face of the earth forever.|source=Legendary and Warner Bros.<ref name=\"Press Release\"/>}}\n\n== Cast ==\n*[[Alexander Skarsg\u00e5rd]]:<br>A [[geologist]] who works closely with Kong. Skarsg\u00e5rd described his character as a [[reluctant hero]] who is \"not an alpha, bad-ass\" and \"thrown into this very dangerous situation and is definitely not equipped for it\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://etcanada.com/news/383733/alexander-skarsgard-spills-details-about-his-role-in-godzilla-vs-king-kong/|title=Alexander Skarsgard Spills Details About His Role In \u2018Godzilla Vs. Kong\u2019|author=Brent Furdyk|work=Entertainment Tonight Canada|date=November 5, 2018|accessdate=October 14, 2019|url-status=live|archivedate=October 14, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191015021004/https://etcanada.com/news/383733/alexander-skarsgard-spills-details-about-his-role-in-godzilla-vs-king-kong/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collider.com/alexander-skarsgard-the-kill-team-the-stand-godzilla-vs-kong-interview/|title=Alexander Skarsgard on 'The Kill Team', 'The Stand', and His Unlikely Hero in 'Godzilla vs. Kong'|last=Radish|first=Christina|date=2019-10-30|website=Collider|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/18/movies/alexander-skarsgard-the-kill-team.html|title=There Are Worse Roles Than the Seducer. Ask Alexander Skarsgard.|last=Shattuck|first=Kathryn|date=2019-10-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-11-09|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*[[Millie Bobby Brown]] as Madison Russell\n*[[Rebecca Hall]]\n*[[Brian Tyree Henry]]\n*[[Shun Oguri]]\n*[[Eiza Gonz\u00e1lez]]:<br>Gonz\u00e1lez described her role as a \"very smart woman behind a company\". She also described the film as \"slightly comedic\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collider.com/eiza-gonzalez-bloodshot-paradise-hills-interview/|title=Eiza Gonz\u00e1lez on 'Paradise Hills' and Playing the First Female Mexican Superhero in 'Bloodshot'|last=Radish|first=Christina|date=2019-10-31|website=Collider|language=en-US|url-status=live|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n*[[Jessica Henwick]]\n*[[Julian Dennison]]\n*[[Kyle Chandler]] as Dr. Mark Russell:<br>Madison's father and an expert [[Anthrozoology|anthrozoologist]].\n*[[Demi\u00e1n Bichir]]\n\nAdditionally, [[Zhang Ziyi]] reprises her role from ''Godzilla: King of the Monsters'', with Van Marten cast as her assistant. [[Lance Reddick]] has been cast in an undisclosed role.\n\n== Production ==\n'''Production credits'''<ref name=\"Press Release\"/>\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Adam Wingard]] \u2013 director\n* Kenji Okuhira \u2013 executive producer\n* [[Yoshimitsu Banno]] \u2013 executive producer (posthumous)\n* [[Jon Jashni]] \u2013 executive producer\n* [[Thomas Tull]] \u2013 executive producer\n* Jay Ashenfelter \u2013 co-producer\n* Jen Conroy \u2013 co-producer\n* Tamara Kent \u2013 co-producer\n* Owen Patterson \u2013 production designer\n* Tom Hammock \u2013 production designer\n* Ann Foley \u2013 costume designer\n* John \u201cDJ\u201d DesJardin \u2013 VFX supervisor\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Development===\nIn September 2015, Legendary moved ''Kong: Skull Island'' from Universal to Warner Bros., which sparked media speculation that [[Godzilla]] and [[King Kong]] would appear in a film together.<ref name=\"KingKongOnMove\">{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2015/09/king-kong-godzilla-legendary-monster-movie-warner-bros-1201521004/ |title=King Kong On Move To Warner Bros, Presaging Godzilla Monster Matchup |last=Fleming Jr. |first=Mike |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=September 10, 2015 |accessdate=September 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150911232832/http://deadline.com/2015/09/king-kong-godzilla-legendary-monster-movie-warner-bros-1201521004/#|archive-date=September 11, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=The Hollywood Reporter |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/hollywood-gorilla-warfare-s-universal-823715 |title=Hollywood Gorilla Warfare: It\u2019s Universal vs. Legendary Over \u2018Kong: Skull Island\u2019 (and Who Says \"Thank You\") |first=Kim |last=Masters |date=September 16, 2015 |accessdate=September 17, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150917235805/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/hollywood-gorilla-warfare-s-universal-823715# |archive-date=September 17, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> In October 2015, Legendary confirmed that they would unite Godzilla and King Kong in ''Godzilla vs. Kong'', at the time targeted for a May 29, 2020, release. Legendary plans to create a shared cinematic franchise \"centered around Monarch\" that \"brings together Godzilla and Legendary\u2019s King Kong in an ecosystem of other [[kaiju|giant super-species]], both classic and new.\"<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.legendary.com/legendary-and-warner-bros-pictures-announce-cinematic-franchise-uniting-godzilla-king-kong-and-other-iconic-giant-monsters/ |title=Legendary and Warner Bros. Pictures Announce Cinematic Franchise Uniting Godzilla, King Kong and Other Iconic Giant Monsters |publisher=Legendary Pictures |date=October 14, 2015 |accessdate=October 14, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105182819/http://www.legendary.com/legendary-and-warner-bros-pictures-announce-cinematic-franchise-uniting-godzilla-king-kong-and-other-iconic-giant-monsters/#|archive-date=November 5, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Producer Alex Garcia confirmed that the film will not be a [[remake]] of ''[[King Kong vs. Godzilla]]'', stating, \"the idea is not to remake that movie.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tohokingdom.com/interviews/kong_alex_garcia_02-2017.html |title=Interview: Alex Garcia \u2013 Roundtable (2015) |last=Mirjahangir |first=Chris |website=Toho Kingdom |date=December 2, 2015 |accessdate=July 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170619160700/http://www.tohokingdom.com/interviews/kong_alex_garcia_02-2017.html#|archive-date=June 19, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2017, [[Adam Wingard]] was announced as the director for ''Godzilla vs. Kong''.<ref name=\"Adam\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/godzilla-kong-finds-director-adam-wingard-1008773 |title='Godzilla vs. Kong' Finds Its Director With Adam Wingard (Exclusive) |last=Kit |first=Borys |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=May 30, 2017 |accessdate=May 30, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531025423/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/godzilla-kong-finds-director-adam-wingard-1008773#|archive-date=May 31, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, Wingard spoke about the outline created by the writers room, stating, \"We're going in very great detail through all the characters, the arcs they have, how they relate to one another, and most importantly how they relate to the monsters, and how the monsters relate to them or reflect them.\" He also stated that he and his team are going \"beat by beat\" on the outline, stating, \"So once again, it's a discussion, and about feeling out how to make it as strong as possible, so that when Terry [Rossio] goes to write the screenplay, he has a definitive breakdown of what to include.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://birthmoviesdeath.com/2017/07/20/adam-wingard-talks-godzilla-vs.-kong-and-directorial-freedom |title=Adam Wingard Talks Godzilla vs. Kong And Directorial Freedom |last=Gingold |first=Michael |work=Birth.Movies.Death |date=July 20, 2017 |accessdate=July 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170723234247/http://birthmoviesdeath.com/2017/07/20/adam-wingard-talks-godzilla-vs.-kong-and-directorial-freedom#|archive-date=July 23, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In August 2017, Wingard spoke about his approach for the monsters, stating:\n\n{{Quote|\"I really want you to take those characters seriously. I want you to be emotionally invested, not just in the human characters, but actually in the monsters. It\u2019s a massive monster brawl movie. There\u2019s lots of monsters going crazy on each other, but at the end of the day I want there to be an emotional drive to it. I want you to be emotionally invested in them. I think that\u2019s what\u2019s going to make it really cool.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://screencrush.com/adam-wingard-godzilla-vs-kong-emotional/ |title=Adam Wingard Wants 'Godzilla vs. Kong' to Make You Cry |last=Whitney |first=E. Oliver |work=Screen Crush |date=August 18, 2017 |accessdate=August 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819034438/http://screencrush.com/adam-wingard-godzilla-vs-kong-emotional/#|archive-date=2017-08-19|url-status=live}}</ref>}} Wingard expressed his desire for the film to have a definite winner, stating:\n\n{{Quote|\u201cI do want there to be a winner. The original film was very fun, but you feel a little let down that the movie doesn\u2019t take a definitive stance. People are still debating now who won in that original movie, you know. So, I do want people to walk away from this film feeling like, Okay, there is a winner.\u201d<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indiewire.com/2017/08/godzilla-vs-kong-adam-wingard-winner-1201868084/ |title=\u2018Godzilla vs. Kong\u2019: Adam Wingard Says the Epic Battle Will Have a Definitive Winner |last=Nordine |first=Michael |work=IndieWire |date=August 20, 2017 |accessdate=January 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109121908/http://www.indiewire.com/2017/08/godzilla-vs-kong-adam-wingard-winner-1201868084/#|archive-date=2018-01-09|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n\nWingard also confirmed that the film will tie in with ''[[Godzilla: King of the Monsters (2019 film)|Godzilla: King of the Monsters]]'', be set in modern times, and feature a \"more rugged, a bit more aged Kong.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://screenrant.com/godzilla-vs-kong-setting-character-details/?view=lista |title=Godzilla vs. Kong Set in Modern Day, Ties to Godzilla 2 |last=Mithaiwala |first=Mansoor |work=Screen Rant |date=August 22, 2017 |accessdate=August 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171224101315/https://screenrant.com/godzilla-vs-kong-setting-character-details/?view=lista#|archive-date=December 24, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Writing===\nIn March 2017, Legendary assembled a writers room to develop the story for ''Godzilla vs. Kong'', with [[Terry Rossio]] (who co-wrote an early unproduced script for [[Godzilla (1998 film)|TriStar's ''Godzilla'']])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scifijapan.com/articles/2015/05/10/godzilla-unmade-the-history-of-jan-de-bonts-unproduced-tristar-film-part-1/ |title=Godzilla Unmade: The History of Jan De Bont\u2019s Unproduced TriStar Film \u2013 Part 1 of 4 |last=Aiken |first=Keith |website=Scifi Japan |date=May 10, 2015 |accessdate=May 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170915071019/http://www.scifijapan.com/articles/2015/05/10/godzilla-unmade-the-history-of-jan-de-bonts-unproduced-tristar-film-part-1/#|archive-date=September 15, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> leading a team consisting of Patrick McKay, J. D. Payne, Lindsey Beer, Cat Vasko, [[T.S. Nowlin]], Jack Paglen, and [[J. Michael Straczynski]].<ref name=\"writers room\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/kong-skull-island-sequel-plans-godzilla-kong-sets-writers-room-984992 |title='Godzilla vs. Kong' Film Sets Writers Room (Exclusive) |last=Kit |first=Borys |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=March 10, 2017 |accessdate=March 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170310230537/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/kong-skull-island-sequel-plans-godzilla-kong-sets-writers-room-984992#|archive-date=March 10, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On his experience with the writers room, Rossio stated:\n\n{{Quote|\"''Godzilla vs. Kong'' was my first experience running a writer's room, and it was fantastic. It was a blast reading samples, meeting different writers, and crafting a story in a group setting. It felt similar to animation, where the film is happening up on the walls, and the end result is better than any one person could accomplish on their own.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/pirates-caribbean-screenwriter-how-a-budget-crisis-changed-villains-1001860 |title=Original 'Pirates of the Caribbean' Screenwriter on How a Budget Crisis Changed the Villains |last=Schoellkopf |first=Christina |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=May 26, 2017 |accessdate=May 27, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170527023430/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/pirates-caribbean-screenwriter-how-a-budget-crisis-changed-villains-1001860#|archive-date=May 27, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n\n[[Michael Dougherty]] and Zach Shields, the director and co-writers of ''Godzilla: King of the Monsters'', provided rewrites to ensure that certain themes from ''King of the Monsters'' were carried over and that some characters were properly developed.<ref>{{cite web |last=Tyler |first=Jacob |url=https://thegww.com/godzilla-vs-kong-got-rewrites-from-mike-dougherty-zach-shields-godzilla-king-of-the-monsters/ |title=''Godzilla vs. Kong'' Got Rewrites From Mike Dougherty & Zach Shields |date=March 5, 2019 |work=Omega Underground |accessdate=March 13, 2019|url-status=live |archivedate=March 13, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190314023922/https://thegww.com/godzilla-vs-kong-got-rewrites-from-mike-dougherty-zach-shields-godzilla-king-of-the-monsters/}}</ref> Dougherty revealed how he wrote for the title characters, and how the film would address their differing interactions with people. For Kong, Dougherty stated the film would feature \"those very unique, and even warm, bonding moments\" between Kong and humans since they've been a staple of the character since the [[King Kong (1933 film)|1933 film]]. For Godzilla, his connection to humans would be \"more implied\" as his softer side is rarely shown.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://screenrant.com/godzilla-king-kong-different-humanity-connections-explained/ |title=Godzilla 2 Director Explains Godzilla & Kong's Different Connections to Humanity |first=Daniel |last=Alvarez |work=Screen Rant |date=May 5, 2019 |accessdate=May 7, 2019|url-status=live |archivedate=May 7, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190507185131/https://screenrant.com/godzilla-king-kong-different-humanity-connections-explained/}}</ref>\n\n=== Pre-production ===\nIn June 2017, it was announced that [[Ziyi Zhang]] had joined Legendary's MonsterVerse, having a reportedly \"pivotal\" role in both ''Godzilla: King of the Monsters'' and ''Godzilla vs. Kong''.<ref name=\"ZiyiCast\">{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2017/06/zhang-ziyi-godzilla-movie-franchise-casting-1202110018/ |title=Zhang Ziyi Comes Aboard 'Godzilla' And Beyond |last=Hipes |first=Patrick |website=Deadline.com |date=June 8, 2017 |accessdate=June 8, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170611233620/http://deadline.com/2017/06/zhang-ziyi-godzilla-movie-franchise-casting-1202110018/#|archive-date=June 11, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In June 2018, [[Julian Dennison]] was cast alongside Van Marten, while [[Millie Bobby Brown]] and [[Kyle Chandler]] would reprise their roles from ''Godzilla: King of the Monsters''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Perez |first=Lexy |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/deadpool-2-star-julian-dennison-joins-godzilla-kong-1116661 |title=''Deadpool 2'' Star Julian Dennison Joins ''Godzilla vs. Kong'' |date=June 2, 2018 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=June 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180603033211/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/deadpool-2-star-julian-dennison-joins-godzilla-kong-1116661#|archive-date=June 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Legendary also sent an offer to [[Frances McDormand]] for a role.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thathashtagshow.com/2018/06/exclusive-deadpool-2-julian-dennison-joins-godzilla-vs-kong/ |title=Exclusive: \u2018Deadpool 2\u2019s\u2019 Julian Dennison Joins \u2018Godzilla vs. Kong\u2019 |last=Murphy |first=Charles |work=That Hashtag Show |date=June 1, 2018 |accessdate=June 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612143532/http://thathashtagshow.com/2018/06/exclusive-deadpool-2-julian-dennison-joins-godzilla-vs-kong/|archive-date=June 12, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> In July 2018, it was revealed that [[Danai Gurira]] was in early talks to join the film.<ref name=\"Danai Guiridia\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/danai-gurira-godzilla-vs-kong-star-trek-the-walking-dead-black-panther-1202425900/ |title=Danai Gurira In Early \u2018Godzilla Vs. Kong\u2019 Talks As \u2018Star Trek\u2019 Also Looms For \u2018Walking Dead\u2019 & \u2018Black Panther\u2019 Star |first=Mike |last=Fleming Jr. |work=Deadline |date=July 12, 2018 |accessdate=July 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180713054816/https://deadline.com/2018/07/danai-gurira-godzilla-vs-kong-star-trek-the-walking-dead-black-panther-1202425900/#|archive-date=July 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In October 2018, [[Brian Tyree Henry]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/brian-tyree-henry-godzilla-vs-kong-millie-bobby-brown-1202976259/ |title=Brian Tyree Henry to Co-Star With Millie Bobby Brown in \u2018Godzilla vs. Kong\u2019 (Exclusive) |first=Justin |last=Kroll |work=Variety |date=October 10, 2018 |accessdate=October 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011014559/https://variety.com/2018/film/news/brian-tyree-henry-godzilla-vs-kong-millie-bobby-brown-1202976259/#|archive-date=October 11, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Demi\u00e1n Bichir]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Kit |first=Borys |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/demi-n-bichir-joining-millie-bobby-brown-godzilla-kong-1153121 |title=Demi\u00e1n Bichir Joining Millie Bobby Brown in ''Godzilla vs. Kong'' |date=October 17, 2018 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |publisher=[[Valence Media]] |accessdate=October 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017213127/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/demi-n-bichir-joining-millie-bobby-brown-godzilla-kong-1153121|archive-date=October 17, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Alexander Skarsg\u00e5rd]],<ref name=\"Skarsg\u00e5rdCast\">{{cite news |last1=Jr |first1=Mike Fleming |title=Alexander Skarsg\u00e5rd To Star In \u2018Godzilla Vs. Kong\u2019 |url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/alexander-skarsgard-to-star-in-godzilla-vs-kong-1202489612/ |accessdate=October 25, 2018 |work=Deadline |date=October 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181026064527/https://deadline.com/2018/10/alexander-skarsgard-to-star-in-godzilla-vs-kong-1202489612/# |archive-date=October 26, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Eiza Gonz\u00e1lez]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/eiza-gonzalez-godzilla-vs-king-kong-alexander-skarsgard-1202492406/ |title=Eiza Gonzalez Joins \u2018Godzilla Vs. King Kong |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |first=Mike |last=Fleming Jr |date=October 30, 2018 |accessdate=October 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031052347/https://deadline.com/2018/10/eiza-gonzalez-godzilla-vs-king-kong-alexander-skarsgard-1202492406/#|archive-date=October 31, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Rebecca Hall]] were added to the cast.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/rebecca-hall-godzilla-vs-kong-1203014950/ |title=Rebecca Hall to Star Opposite Millie Bobby Brown in \u2018Godzilla vs. Kong\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE) |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |first=Justin |last=Kroll |date=October 30, 2018 |accessdate=October 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031005404/https://variety.com/2018/film/news/rebecca-hall-godzilla-vs-kong-1203014950/#|archive-date=October 31, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In November 2018, [[Jessica Henwick]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/jessica-henwick-godzilla-vs-kong-game-of-thrones-1203024081/ |title=\u2018Game of Thrones\u2019 Actress Jessica Henwick Joins \u2018Godzilla vs. Kong\u2019 (Exclusive) |first=Justin |last=Kroll |work=Variety |date=November 8, 2018 |accessdate=November 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181109070757/https://variety.com/2018/film/news/jessica-henwick-godzilla-vs-kong-game-of-thrones-1203024081/|archive-date=November 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Shun Oguri]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/shun-oguri-godzilla-vs-kong-japanese-star-crows-zero-alexander-skarsgard-1202499759/ |title=Japanese Star Shun Oguri Makes Hollywood Debut In \u2018Godzilla Vs. Kong\u2019 |first=Mike |last=Fleming Jr |work=Deadline |date=November 11, 2018 |accessdate=November 11, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181111213802/https://deadline.com/2018/11/shun-oguri-godzilla-vs-kong-japanese-star-crows-zero-alexander-skarsgard-1202499759/#|archive-date=November 11, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Lance Reddick]] were cast, with Oguri making his Hollywood debut.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/bosch-lance-reddick-godzilla-vs-kong-1202502022/ |title='Bosch' Actor Lance Reddick Cast in 'Godzilla vs Kong' |website=Deadline |first=Amanda |last=N'Duka |date=November 14, 2018 |accessdate=November 14, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115030528/https://deadline.com/2018/11/bosch-lance-reddick-godzilla-vs-kong-1202502022/|archive-date=November 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[Principal photography]] began on November 12, 2018 in [[Hawaii]] and [[Australia]] and was expected to end in February 2019 under the working title ''Apex''.<ref name=\"Press Release\">{{cite web |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20181112005664/en/Warner-Bros.-Pictures%E2%80%99-Legendary-Entertainment%E2%80%99s-Monsterverse-Shifts |title=Warner Bros. Pictures\u2019 and Legendary Entertainment\u2019s Monsterverse Shifts into Overdrive as Cameras Roll on the Next Big-Screen Adventure \"Godzilla Vs. Kong\" |work=Business Wire |date= |accessdate=November 12, 2018 |archivedate=January 19, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190120054526/https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20181112005664/en/Warner-Bros.-Pictures%E2%80%99-Legendary-Entertainment%E2%80%99s-Monsterverse-Shifts|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Prasad |first=R.A |url=https://pursuenews.com/godzilla-vs-kong-working-title-revealed/ |title=Warner Bros. And Legendary Pictures' ''Godzilla Vs. Kong'' Working Title Revealed |date=May 3, 2018 |publisher=PureNews |accessdate=May 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504092023/https://pursuenews.com/godzilla-vs-kong-working-title-revealed/#|archive-date=May 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Production was initially slated to begin on October 1, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marc |first1=Christopher |title='Godzilla vs Kong' Heading Back To Australia and Hawaii - GWW |url=https://thegww.com/godzilla-vs-kong-heading-back-to-australia-and-hawaii/ |accessdate=July 18, 2018 |work=GWW |date=July 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011053715/https://thegww.com/godzilla-vs-kong-heading-back-to-australia-and-hawaii/# |archive-date=October 11, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> For the Hawaii shoot, the crew filmed on the [[USS Missouri (BB-63)|USS ''Missouri'']], at [[Manoa Falls]], and in [[Downtown Honolulu]]. The crew established a camp in the [[Hawaii Route 72|Kalanianaole Highway]], which had been closed until November 21. Local crews and extras were used for the film.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2018/11/16/hawaii-news/godzilla-vs-kong-filming-in-full-swing-with-upcoming-closures-on-oahu/ |title=\u2018Godzilla vs. Kong\u2019 filming in full swing with upcoming closures on Oahu |first=Nina |last=Wu |work=Star Advertiser |date=November 17, 2018 |accessdate=November 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181117114833/http://www.staradvertiser.com/2018/11/16/hawaii-news/godzilla-vs-kong-filming-in-full-swing-with-upcoming-closures-on-oahu/|archive-date=November 17, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2019, filming resumed in [[Gold Coast, Queensland]] at [[Village Roadshow Studios]] for an additional 26 weeks.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/godzilla-vs-kong-begins-filming-on-the-gold-coast-20190118-p50s6d.html |title=Godzilla vs. Kong begins filming on the Gold Coast |first=Felicity |last=Caldwell |work=Brisbane Times |date=January 18, 2019 |accessdate=January 19, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119224354/https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/godzilla-vs-kong-begins-filming-on-the-gold-coast-20190118-p50s6d.html |archivedate=January 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Godzilla sighting down under! |url=https://moviehole.net/godzilla-sighting-down-under/ |website=Moviehole |publisher=Editorial Staff |accessdate=January 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190124034500/https://moviehole.net/godzilla-sighting-down-under/ |archive-date=January 24, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFilming locations in Australia included [[Miami State High School]] and parts of [[Brisbane]] such as the [[Newstead, Queensland|Newstead suburb]], the [[Chinatown, Brisbane|Chinatown Mall in Fortitude Valley]], and the [[Wickham Terrace Car Park]]. In April 2019, Wingard confirmed via [[Instagram]] that filming in Australia had wrapped.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2470013/Godzilla-Vs-Kong-Has-Wrapped-In-Australia-According-To-The-Director |title=Godzilla Vs. Kong Has Wrapped In Australia |first=Dirk |last=Libbey |work=Cinema Blend |date=April 9, 2019 |accessdate=April 9, 2019|url-status=live |archivedate=April 9, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410020411/https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2470013/Godzilla-Vs-Kong-Has-Wrapped-In-Australia-According-To-The-Director}}</ref> That same month, Wingard revealed [[Hong Kong]] as one of the final shooting locations and that principal photography had wrapped.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/movies/2019/04/20/godzilla-vs-kong/ |title=Godzilla vs. Kong wraps shooting |first=Clark |last=Collis |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=April 20, 2019 |accessdate=April 20, 2019|url-status=live |archivedate=April 20, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190420223019/https://ew.com/movies/2019/04/20/godzilla-vs-kong/}}</ref>Thank you for reading\n\n== Release ==\n===Marketing===\nIn May 2019, the first promotional one-sheet poster was revealed at the Licensing Expo.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://collider.com/godzilla-vs-kong-dune-promo-posters/ |title=New Promo Posters for \u2018Godzilla vs Kong\u2019 and \u2018Dune\u2019 Tease the Titanic 2020 Titles |first=Dave |last=Trumbore |work=Collider |date=May 30, 2019 |accessdate=May 31, 2019|url-status=live |archivedate=May 31, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531091732/http://collider.com/godzilla-vs-kong-dune-promo-posters/}}</ref> In June 2019, Warner Bros screened an early look to European exhibitors at CineEurope.<ref name=\"CineEurope\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/warner-bros-godzilla-vs-kong-it2-joker-wonder-woman-lionsgate-rian-johnson-knives-out-studiocanal-cineeurope-1202633778/ |title=Warner Bros Teases Horror, DC, \u2018Godzilla Vs Kong\u2019; Studiocanal Goes \u2018Radioactive\u2019 \u2013 CineEurope |first=Nancy |last=Tartaglione |work=Deadline Hollywood |date=June 17, 2019 |accessdate=June 17, 2019|url-status=live |archivedate=June 17, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618043628/https://deadline.com/2019/06/warner-bros-godzilla-vs-kong-it2-joker-wonder-woman-lionsgate-rian-johnson-knives-out-studiocanal-cineeurope-1202633778/}}</ref> In August 2019, it was announced that Disruptor Beam will develop a mobile game to tie-in for the film's release.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cosmicbook.news/godzilla-vs-kong-poster-game |title=Godzilla vs. Kong Poster teases one will fall;Game in Development |first=Matt |last=McGloin |work=Cosmic Book News |date=August 10, 2019 |accessdate=August 11, 2019|url-status=live |archivedate=August 11, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811215337/https://cosmicbook.news/godzilla-vs-kong-poster-game}}</ref> In December 2019, a brief clip was revealed during a Warner Bros. reel at [[Comic Con Experience]], and later leaked online.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2486314/whoa-kong-punches-godzilla-in-super-brief-but-badass-godzilla-vs-kong-footage|title=Whoa, Kong Punches Godzilla In Super-Brief But Badass Godzilla Vs. Kong Footage|author=Gina Carbone|work=CinemaBlend|date=December 8, 2019|accessdate=December 8, 2019|url-status=live|archivedate=December 8, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209011305/https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2486314/whoa-kong-punches-godzilla-in-super-brief-but-badass-godzilla-vs-kong-footage}}</ref> In January 2020, images from the Hong Kong Toys & Games Fair displaying figures (including a [[Mechagodzilla]] figure) related to the film were leaked online, sparking speculation whether the film would include Mechagodzilla.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2487983/godzilla-vs-kong-might-be-bringing-in-an-iconic-kaiju|title=Godzilla Vs. Kong Might Be Bringing In An Iconic Kaiju|author=Adam Holmes|work=Cinema Blend|date=January 7, 2020|accessdate=January 7, 2020|url-status=live|archivedate=January 7, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108042635/https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2487983/godzilla-vs-kong-might-be-bringing-in-an-iconic-kaiju}}</ref> In February 2020, Toho and Legendary announced the ''Godzilla vs. Kong'' Publishing Program and licensees. Through the publishing program, Legendary plans to release two graphic novels, an art book, novelizations, and children\u2019s books. Amongst the licensees named were [[Playmates Toys]], Bioworld, Rubies, Funko, 60Out, and the Virtual Reality Company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scifijapan.com/articles/2020/02/20/toho-and-legendary-announce-licensees-for-godzilla-vs-kong/|title=Toho and Legendary Announce Licensees for Godzilla vs. Kong|author1=Chris Mowry|author2=Jacara Jenkins|work=SciFi Japan|date=February 20, 2020|accessdate=February 20, 2020|url-status=live|archivedate=February 20, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221062043/http://www.scifijapan.com/articles/2020/02/20/toho-and-legendary-announce-licensees-for-godzilla-vs-kong/}}</ref>\n\n===Theatrical===\n''Godzilla vs. Kong'' is scheduled to be released in the United States on November 20, 2020, in 2D, [[3D film|3D]], and [[IMAX]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/godzilla-kong-release-date-pushed-8-months-november-2020-1253500|title='Godzilla vs. Kong' Release Date Pushed 8 Months to November 2020|author=Aaron Couch|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=November 25, 2019|accessdate=November 25, 2019|url-status=live|archivedate=November 25, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191126074636/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/godzilla-kong-release-date-pushed-8-months-november-2020-1253500}}</ref> It will be distributed by [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Pictures]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/space-jam-2-release-date-godzilla-vs-kong-annabelle-sequel-warner-bros-1202562428/ |title=Warner Bros Dates \u2018Space Jam 2\u2019, Shifts \u2018Annabelle\u2019 Sequel & \u2018Godzilla Vs. Kong\u2019 |first=Erik |last=Pedersen |work=Deadline |date=February 21, 2019 |accessdate=February 21, 2019|url-status=live |archivedate=February 21, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222025700/https://deadline.com/2019/02/space-jam-2-release-date-godzilla-vs-kong-annabelle-sequel-warner-bros-1202562428/}}</ref> except in Japan where it will be distributed by [[Toho]].<ref name=\"Press Release\"/> The film was previously scheduled to be released on May 29, May 22, and March 13, 2020.<ref name=\"May10\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/warner-bros-moves-dates-godzilla-892634 |title=Warner Bros. Moves Dates For 'Godzilla 2,' 'Godzilla vs Kong' |last=Rahman |first=Abid |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=May 10, 2016 |accessdate=May 10, 2016|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6pLyTqstH?url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/warner-bros-moves-dates-godzilla-892634#|archive-date=March 30, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/warner-studio-toby-emmerich-peter-roth-dc-netflix-godzilla-vs-kong-kevin-tsujihara-1202629538/ |title=Warner Bros. Bosses Toby Emmerich & Peter Roth On Studio Post Kevin Tsujihara In Streaming Era, Disney/Fox & Potential \u2018Godzilla vs. Kong\u2019 Move \u2013 Produced By |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |work=Deadline Hollywood |date=June 8, 2019 |accessdate=June 9, 2019|url-status=live |archivedate=June 9, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190609070404/https://deadline.com/2019/06/warner-studio-toby-emmerich-peter-roth-dc-netflix-godzilla-vs-kong-kevin-tsujihara-1202629538/}}</ref><ref name=\"new date\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/space-jam-2-release-date-godzilla-vs-kong-annabelle-sequel-warner-bros-1202562428/ |title=Warner Bros Dates \u2018Space Jam 2\u2019, Shifts \u2018Annabelle\u2019 Sequel & \u2018Godzilla Vs. Kong\u2019 |last=Pedersen |first=Erik |work=Deadline |date=February 21, 2019 |accessdate=February 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222025700/https://deadline.com/2019/02/space-jam-2-release-date-godzilla-vs-kong-annabelle-sequel-warner-bros-1202562428/|archive-date=February 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In February 2020, Warner Bros. hosted an unannounced test screening, which received a positive response.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2491108/check-out-godzilla-vs-kongs-directors-cryptic-post-following-reported-test-screening|title=Check Out Godzilla Vs. Kong's Director\u2019s Cryptic Post Following Reported Test Screening|author=Adam Holmes|work=Cinema Blend|date=February 28, 2020|accessdate=March 11, 2020|url-status=live|archivedate=March 11, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312012236/https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2491108/check-out-godzilla-vs-kongs-directors-cryptic-post-following-reported-test-screening}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist|refs=}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{cite book |last=Kalat |first=David |year=2010 |title=A Critical History and Filmography of Toho's Godzilla Series - Second Edition |publisher=McFarland |isbn=9780786447497 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|5034838|Godzilla vs. Kong}}\n{{MonsterVerse}}\n{{Godzilla}}\n{{KingKong}}\n{{Adam Wingard}}\n\n[[Category:Upcoming films]]\n[[Category:2020 films]]\n[[Category:2020 3D films]]\n[[Category:2020s monster movies]]\n[[Category:2020s sequel films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American 3D films]]\n[[Category:Crossover films]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Atlantic Ocean]]\n[[Category:Films set in Berlin]]\n[[Category:Films set in Brisbane]]\n[[Category:Films set in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Films set in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Films set in Honolulu]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Films set in Moscow]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Pacific Ocean]]\n[[Category:Films set in Paris]]\n[[Category:Films set in Rome]]\n[[Category:Films set in Seoul]]\n[[Category:Films set in Shanghai]]\n[[Category:Films set in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Films set in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Films set in Tokyo]]\